<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Largest Exhibition Venue Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Expo, the largest
exhibition venue in Asia, was officially opened Monday as part of
the achievements the Singapore government has made in promoting
the exhibition industry and turning the city state into an
exhibition hub in the world as well as in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the joint opening of the Singapore Expo and Food &AMP;
Hotel Asia 2000 in the evening, acting Singapore Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong said, "The international exhibition industry looks
set for further growth in the years to come. With the Singapore
Expo, we now have the infrastructure and supporting systems in
place to ride the wave."
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Expo, built at a cost of 220 million Singapore
dollars (about 130 million U.S. dollars), offers 60,000 square
meters of column-free indoor exhibition space, 20,000 square
meters of outdoor exhibition space, 10 well-equipped conference
rooms of various sizes and nine meeting rooms.
</P>
<P>
The indoor space is divided into six inter-connected halls,
each with its own meeting room and food and beverage outlets and
its ground-level exhibition halls facilitate easy movement of move-
in and move-out operation, saving a lot money and time. In
addition, it is fully equipped with state-of-the-art exhibition
and conference facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Expo is also equipped with 2,200 dedicated
parking lots for visitors/exhibitors who drive and two taxi stands
for the convenience of other visitors.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition venue, owned by the Ministry of Trade and
Industry and managed by the Port of Singapore Authority
Corporation Ltd., started operation in March 1999 and hosted more
than 55 major international exhibitions last year.
</P>
<P>
In an average month, it hosts five events with a total
attendance of 30,000 visitors. However, it attracted a record
number of events and visitors in March 2000 hosting 15 events
attended by some 100,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
Lee revealed in his speech that some 90 trade and consumer
exhibitions, out of which 75 are international, will be held at
the center this year.
</P>
<P>
By the mid-1990s, Singapore was hosting more than 100
exhibitions every year, which attracted more than 200,000 overseas
exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
Lee also said his government will continue to promote the
exhibition industry as it is a significant source of tourism
revenues for Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"The Meeting, Incentives, Conventions and Exhibitions or 'MICE'
sector brings in up to 400,000 overseas visitors annually," Lee
said, adding that they spend on average three times as much as
other visitors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the food &AMP; Hotel Asia 2000, which will open to the
public Tuesday and occupies all the six halls at the Singapore
Expo, brings together some 2,500 participants from 67 countries
and areas and its showcasing of the latest products in the food
and hospitality sector is expected to attract 16,000 overseas and
28,000 local visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
