<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Progress Slow Since Inception: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Experts in Bangladesh Monday noted
that the process of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation(SAARC) to achieve its coveted objectives has
progressed slowly since its inception in 1985 due to many problems.
</P>
<P>
At a roundtable here, they identified bureaucracy, the arms
race,the nuclear threat, the Kashmir issue, trade barriers, trade
imbalance,bilateral disputes, lack of initiatives at the regional
level, the weak institutional shape of the SAARC Secretariat and
lack of contact with other regional bodies as major impediments
that have slowed the process of SAARC's desired progress.
</P>
<P>
A good number of academicians and development thinkers were
present at the roundtable on "SAARC Process and Regional
Cooperation in South Asia" organized by Bangladesh Institute of
International and Strategic Studies (BIISS). BIISS Director
General Ahsan was in the chair.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Ahsan said that over the last 15 years, SAARC
has developed some institutional capacity but it still needs an
effective platform for sustainable cooperation among the member
countries.
</P>
<P>
Former Foreign Secretary Farooq Sobhan said SAARC could not
progress due to a number of problems.
</P>
<P>
"If we could remove the trade barriers, SAARC would progress
substantially in both trade and investment fields since the region
itself has been trying to have common trade and investment regimes,
"he said.
</P>
<P>
He also referred to the recent visit of U.S. President Bill
Clinton to South Asia and said it had, in fact, opened a door
toward encouraging the need for better and more prospective
regional cooperation among the seven countries within the SAARC
framework.
</P>
<P>
Zaidi Sattar of the World Bank said that despite trade and non-
trade barriers created by the governments in this region, natural
tendencies are taking place toward enhanced trade and business
among the nations.
</P>
<P>
"Bilateral trade balance is not an issue but regional trade
balance is important for a solid cooperation among the nations
here,"he observed.
</P>
<P>
In his summing-up address, Sobhan said SAARC is now at the
crossroads facing problems and he urged the governments of the
member countries to increasingly try to improve the regional
cooperation process.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
