<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Amends Laws to Secure Trouble-Free Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's parliament has approved
amendments to laws regulating legislative elections which will take
place later this year with the aim of securing a trouble-free vote,
the country's Middle East News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amendments, approved Monday night by the People's Assembly,
will provide for police to be posted outside each polling station
to prevent intimidation of voters and forestall the kind of
violence that shook previous elections in 1995 when around 60
people died.
</P>
<P>
At that time, Egypt's opposition spoke out against "electoral
fraud," which they claimed had allowed the National Democratic
Party led by President Hosni Mubarak to win 417 of the 454 seats in
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Judicial observers will also be charged with overseeing the
entire electoral process and guarantee fair vote counting in the
elections in 2000, according to the amendments.
</P>
<P>
But members of the opposition Al-Wafd Party rejected the
measures as "insufficient and deceptive." The party had called for
the annulment of laws dating to the era of President Gamal Abdel
Nasser in the 1960s, under which at least 50 percent of the
parliament members must be workers or farmers.
</P>
<P>
But Minister of State for the People's Assembly and the Shura
(Consultative) Council Affairs Kamal Mohamed el-Shazli told the
parliament that the legislation would remain in place.
</P>
<P>
The elections are due to take place in November, but no precise
date has been set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Proposes Summit in March Every Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League has proposed that
the Arab countries convene a summit in March every year, a senior
league official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa al-Fiqqi, Arab League assistant secretary general for
Arab affairs told reporters that the proposal to make a regular
March summit the pan-Arab forum's highest authority would be
discussed on May 24 by the foreign ministers of Egypt, Oman, Syria,
Tunisia and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The five countries form a committee to deal with the issue
concerning the convocation of Arab summits on a regular basis. The
League's 1945 charter does not stipulate the holding of Arab
summits and states that the council of foreign ministers is its
highest body.
</P>
<P>
Al-Fiqqi said the March date has been chosen as the best time
for holding a summit as leaders and foreign ministers are usually
busy later in the year with the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Yemen had earlier proposed holding a regular summit in November
every year. The league's proposal is a combination of ideas put
forward by Yemen and the Cairo-based forum's secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Despite frequent talks about the subject, differences among Arab
states have made no more summit possible since 1996 in Cairo, and
even then Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was not invited because of
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
