<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Foreign Ministers Begin Debate on U.N. Role in New Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the Group
of 77 (G-77) member states Tuesday began an interactive debate on
the role of the United Nations in the 21st century, hoping to
boost the U.N. role in aiding the developing South and prepare for
the Millennium Summit, scheduled for September in New York.
</P>
<P>
The debate will be held behind closed doors until 18:00
Tuesday, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the topic at the opening session of foreign
ministers Tuesday morning, Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe Perez
Roque said, "I hope that our extensive and democratic discussion
will be a clear indication of our aspirations, and at the same
time will contribute to the preparatory work for the Millennium
Summit."
</P>
<P>
The developing South, whose representatives are gathering in
Havana for the largest participation of heads of state and
government in the 36-year history of G-77, has been long calling
for a just and new international political and economic system,
and a bigger U.N. role in working for economic equality between
the South and the North.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leaders of developing countries were drawing up a
call for a new world order meant to help them eradicate poverty
while foreign ministers were proposing calls on rich nations to
forgive debts, increase aid and trade, share new technology and
shift more decision-making power to the United Nations away from
institutions such as the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
"We want to achieve a more democratic and equitable
arrangement," said a draft of the proposed plan of action for the
133-nation body, which is holding its first summit since its
founding in June 1964.
</P>
<P>
About 40 heads of state or government are expected to take
part in the top-level talks scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Ministerial Meeting Starts in Havana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 77's South Summit
started Tuesday in Havana with the meeting of the foreign
ministers of the participating countries.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe Perez Roque said that the South-
South cooperation is of utmost importance, but that the support
from the North is necessary.
</P>
<P>
The ministers analyzed the report they received Monday from the
experts, who discussed the documents that are to be approved by
the moment the Summit is over, Friday.
</P>
<P>
Issues regarding globalization were present during a much of
the deliberations, as well as the possibility of access from the
South to technical knowledge and technology, which the developed
world enjoys almost exclusively at the present.
</P>
<P>
Arthur Mbanefo, president of the Group of 77, pledged Monday an
"interactive" dialogue for an international system more suitable
for the majority of nations, which are the poorest of the world as
well.
</P>
<P>
The United Nation's design for the twenty first century is also
one of the main issues dealt with Tuesday in this capital city by
the foreign ministers of the 133 participating countries within
the G-77.
</P>
<P>
The meeting started Sunday and there will be over 50 leaders
participating. They keep on arriving in this capital along with
ministers and experts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
