<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Calls for North-South Fair Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) pledged Tuesday respectful, fair and mutually
advantageous relations between developed and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
UNDP Public Relations and Communication Director Djibril Diallo
said that two actions can be carried out to change the current
state of the world order.
</P>
<P>
First, rich countries must increase their development
assistance to the less developed countries; second, a solution to
the foreign debt problem.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat regretted that five years after the Copenhagen
1995 Social Development Summit, there are many poor nations still
being affected by severe poverty conditions.
</P>
<P>
He considered the agenda being discussed by the developing
countries as very important during the first G-77 South Summit,
scheduled to take place on April 12-14.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues being covered prior to the beginning of the
Havana Summit are South-South cooperation, unequal North-South
relations, and technological difference between rich and
underdeveloped countries.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP is present in 174 countries and territories, and has
as its main task to advise the governments of the developing
countries, especially in poverty eradication, job creation, and
environment protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
