<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak to Hold Talks With Clinton on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak is starting talks first with high-ranking U.S. officials and
then with President Bill Clinton in the evening in a hope to
salvage the stalled peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who flew in Washington at 3:15 a.m., hurried here to a
summons from President Clinton at a time as the Israel-Palestinian
talks at Bolling Air Force Base near Washington have been balking
with no progress in sight and the Syrian-Israeli talks see no
promise for resumption. And he is now trying to launch another
peace offensive on the Lebanon track by unilateral withdrawal from
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure for Washington, Barak's aides said the
prime minister's priority in the Tuesday evening meeting with
Clinton would be to secure U.S. support for Israel's impending
pull out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The low-level expectation shows that Barak no longer believes
he can meet the ambitious goal of a comprehensive Middle East
peace by year's end.
</P>
<P>
Barak is now meeting with U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross. He
will then meet with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger before seeing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Israel's embassy spokesman Mark Regev said Barak was "very
serious about the series of meetings he has today."
</P>
<P>
With regard to Clinton, he was anxious to secure a Middle East
peace breakthrough before leaving office in nine months.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters that the
president thought it was important to use the meeting with Barak
and the meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat next week as
a chance to "take stock of where they are and keep the process
moving forward."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, meeting at the
Bolling Air Force Base, kept working on an overall settlement as
well as another Israeli pullback on the West Bank scheduled for
June.
</P>
<P>
"So far there are no results," Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO
representative in Washington, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said the Palestinians wanted Clinton to make clear to
Barak that the negotiations must be concluded successfully by
September 13, a deadline set by the United States, Israel and the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
