<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Environment Minister Tables Endangered Species Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Environment Minister
David Anderson tabled an endangered species bill Tuesday in a bid
to intensify protection of animals such as the grizzly bear and
piping plover.
</P>
<P>
The bill suggests fines of up to 1 million Canadian dollars (
about 690,000 U.S. dollars) for corporations and 250,000 dollars (
about 172,500 U.S. dollars) for individuals for killing any of
endangered wildlife.
</P>
<P>
A jail term of five years is also possible for those convicted
of killing endangered species or destroying their habitat under
the new Species at Risk Act introduced in the Commons.
</P>
<P>
The proposed legislation, among others, makes provision for
compensating landowners in case an endangered species happens to
live on their property and causes severe financial losses.
</P>
<P>
Minister Anderson already announced a program in December to
provide private landowners with incentive to preserve endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government was reported to set aside 90 million
Canadian dollars (about 62.1 million U.S. dollars) over three
years in the budget for that purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Favors Just Solution to Cyprus Issue: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia firmly supports a lasting
and just solution to the Cyprus issue, said Russian Ambassador to
Cyprus Vladimir Pavlinov here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with the ruling Democratic Rally party
leader Nicos Anastasiades, Pavlinov said Russia's position on
Cyprus has not changed after Vladimir Putin was elected president
of the Russian Federation last month.
</P>
<P>
"Actually I said whoever is president, head of the government in
Russia, our position on the Cyprus issue is the same," Pavlinov was
quoted as saying by Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the formula for a lasting and just solution of the
Cyprus issue can be worked out during the talks between the leaders
of the Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot communities in the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974, when Turkish troops invaded and occupied 37
percent of Cyprus' northern area after a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
To reunite the divided island, the leaders of the two
communities have already completed two rounds of proximity talks
under United Nations auspices, the first in New York last December
and second in Geneva in February. The third round of such talks are
due to start in New York on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Anastasiades described the meeting with Pavlinov "useful" and
thanked Russia for its position on the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Backs Mideast Peace Process: DM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia always backs the
efforts aimed at establishing a just and comprehensive peace in the
Mideast region, said Saudi Defense Minister Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz
on Tuesday. "We are against any change of this concept," said
the minister at a joint press conference held in the Red Sea port
city of Jeddah with visiting British Secretary of State for Defence
Geoff Hoon.
</P>
<P>
"However, peace cannot be established unless Israel withdraws
fully from the Lebanese and Syrian territories and recognizes the
rights of Lebanese and Syrian peoples as well as the right of
Palestinian refugees to return to their homeland under the U.N.
Security Council resolutions," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Hoon said that Britain and the United States were
committed to maintaining security and peace in the Persian Gulf. He
appreciated contributions by Saudi Arabia in this respect.
</P>
<P>
"Through our cooperation, we can establish a common modern
security and protection system in this region," he underscored.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Saudi Arabia are trying to strengthen their military
and security ties and economic and investment cooperation as well,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The British military chief called on the international community
to exert all necessary efforts to back the Mideast peace process
and expressed his country's readiness to offer any help or
guarantee to this end.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the reported purchase of U.S. warplanes and
development of Saudi infantry troops, Prince Sultan said "We are
developing our troops continuously and we will not stop at any
limit."
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen in Jeddah on Sunday, Sultan discussed a 504-million-U.S.-
dollar deal for the purchase of more than 12 F-15 fighters to
replace older ones.
</P>
<P>
On the reported Saudi mediation between Algeria and Morocco, he
said "I do not think there is a hostility between the two Arab
neighbors that deserves a mediation."
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, King Mohammed VI of Morocco and Algerian
President Abdelaziz Bouteflika are going on the right path towards
rapprochement, he noted, adding "we are just supporters."
</P>
<P>
Morocco and Algeria, two members of the Arab Maghreb Union, have
been quarrelling for years over the Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
Hoon, who arrived in Saudi Arabia for a two-day visit Monday,
has met separately with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, and Crown
Prince and First Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He will continue his tour to Oman later Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
