<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Army Warns of Attacks on North after Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Senior Israel Defense Forces
(IDF) officers Tuesday issued warnings that Israel's northern
border areas would not be quiet after Israeli troops withdraw from
south Lebanon by July, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee, IDF Chief of General Staff Shaul Mofaz said there might
be potential major flare-up of "terrorist attacks" against Israeli
northern settlements after a unilateral pullout from the so-called
security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
To show Israel's determination to revenge in such a case, Mofaz
said that if an uneasy reality emerged along the international
border between Israel and Lebanon, IDF will adopt a clear-cut
policy of deterrence and retaliation.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel will not tolerate any situation that it
redeploys on the basis of U.N. Security Council resolutions but
remains under threats of attacks.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a senior IDF intelligence office also warned that
Palestinian rejectionist groups in Lebanon, which have been in
dormant in recent years, would be reactivated because of the
security vacuum left by the planned pullout.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he told the Knesset committee, there were signs that
Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas, a Shiite Muslim militia fighting to
end Israeli occupation since 1980s, are recruiting "terrorists"
from the 300,000 Palestinian refugees in Lebanese camps.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas, who had killed at least seven IDF soldiers and
wounded dozens since the beginning of this year, want to justify
its attacks against Israel with the Palestinian refugees, as the
office put it.
</P>
<P>
Many of the refugees have been kept in exile for decades because
the wars between Israel and the Arabs since 1948 and desperately
want to go back their homes, a right rejected by Israel till now.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of a Palestinian uprising in south Lebanon reminds
many Israelis of the situation along the border in 1970s and early
80s, which prompted Israel to set up the security zone in 1985 with
a self-claimed aim of preventing cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
But mounting death toll during the 22-year occupation prompted
Israeli cabinet to decide on March 5 to endorse a key pledge by
Prime Minister Ehud Barak to withdraw from the zone by July, with
or without a peace deal with Syria, the major power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
This move was believed aimed at pressuring Syria to return to
the negotiating table, as it would deprive Syria of the major
bargaining chip in their demanded return of the Golan Heights, a
strategic Syrian plateau seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
However, Syrian President Hafez al-Assad did not soften his
stance under pressure, as indicated by his summit with U.S.
President Bill Clinton in Geneva on March 26, which failed to
unblock the stalemate in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
A unilateral withdrawal which the Barak administration seems
determined to pursue in the absence of a security agreement with
Syria and Lebanon, warned some IDF generals, would be dangerous and
bloody.
</P>
<P>
They said they have seen bad omens from a letter sent to U.N
Secretary General Kofi Annan by Lebanese President Emil Lahoud last
week.
</P>
<P>
The letter warned that extremist Palestinian factions in Lebanon
refugee camps are expected to operate against Israel after the
withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
