<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Majlis Gives Municipality Limited Command over Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran's outgoing conservative Majlis
(parliament) on Tuesday rejected a government bill to bring
Tehran's traffic police under the municipality's command, but gave
the city limited administrative rights over the police.
</P>
<P>
By amending the law concerning the security forces, or the
police, the Majlis instructed the traffic police to act under the
directives of the municipality, now under control of pro-
reformists, with the exception of emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
The municipality will provide the traffic police with all
equipment, installations, facilities and financial obligations
except wages and bonus of personnel, telecommunication equipment,
arms and ammunition, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
A by-law on implementation, including the appointment of senior
police officials, will be formulated in six months by the Interior
Ministry in cooperation with the police headquarters and upon
cabinet approval, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
The traffic police have been blamed for its inefficiency in
regulating traffic, a major source of all pollution in the capital
city, and in curbing the rise in road accidents.
</P>
<P>
The government fielded the bill late last year, requesting the
Majlis to allow the municipality to command the traffic police in
order to improve the chaotic traffic situation and reduce air
pollution caused by outworn vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Mayor Moteza Alviri said last year that 72 percent of the
pollution in the city is caused by the traffic. He boasted that
pollution will be sharply decreased if the Majlis puts the traffic
police under his control.
</P>
<P>
The traffic police, like the army and the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps, are under the direct command of the supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who is also commander-in-chief of Iran's
armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
