<HEADLINE> Turkish Business Leaders Envision New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish business leaders on Tuesday
expressed their expectation for a new president who is experienced
in foreign policy and economy.
</P>
<P>
As incumbent President Suleyman Demirel's tenure expires on May
15, the race for the 10th president of Turkey has started. The
candidates should apply to the Parliament Speaker's Office on April
16-25.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government, led by Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit,
suffered a setback last week when parliament rebuffed his efforts
to amend the constitution in order to secure another term for
Demirel, 76.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Turkish business circle said they expected a
president tactful on foreign policy, who can preserve stability in
Turkish internal and external affairs.
</P>
<P>
They said,"Turkey turned its direction to the West. It is a
leader in Turkish-spoken countries as well, so it must maintain
this mission."
</P>
<P>
Fuat Miras, chairman of Turkish Union of Chambers and Trade,
said ,"Turkey has played a role in many international organizations
and global arena. The new president should be able to maintain
Turkey's position in the world and keep existing relations with
other countries."
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the new president will show Turkey's modern
western face to the world in the process from a European Union (EU)
candidate to a full member.
</P>
<P>
Refik Baydur, chairman of Turkish Confederation of Employers'
Unions, said that they expected a respectable president, who can
make himself accepted by the outside world as well.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the new president can succeed in maintaining Turkey's
positive relations with European countries.
</P>
<P>
Other leading business figures said that Turkey must speed up
its economic development on a basis of political stability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's president is elected by parliament for a seven-year
term. The post is largely symbolic, but the president can serve as
a
behind-the-scene power broker, especially in times of crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
