<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes DPRK-S. Korea Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi on Tuesday expressed welcome to a planned summit
meeting between leaders of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) and the Republic of Korea (ROK).
</P>
<P>
Iran hopes the talks would produce tangible and constructive
results in line with the interests of the two peoples in the Korean
peninsula, Asefi was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that the two countries would be able to
solve their outstanding problems and restore peace, security and
unity in the peninsula through talks and understanding.
</P>
<P>
The summit, to be held on June 12-14 in Pyongyang, was announced
jointly by Pyongyang and Seoul on Monday. It will be the first
encounter between the leaders of the two sides since the end of the
Korean War in 1945.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung said Tuesday that the summit
would be a "big step forward" in the peace efforts in the peninsula
though it would be unlikely to resolve any of the major issues
dividing the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The national issues, which have been divisive for a half
century, cannot be resolved overnight," he said, adding that
economic assistance and cooperation, reunions of millions of
separated family members and tension-easing measures will top the
agenda of the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
