<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: The Smile Train Runs Faster in China  (by Xie Meihua) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW ORLEANS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Smile Train in 1999
funded 2,000 cleft surgeries for Chinese children and will fund 4,
000 surgeries in 2000, J. Bexter Urist, president of The Smile
Train, told the press Monday in Computer Associates International
Inc (CA) World 2000 held from April 9-14 in New Orleans, Louisiana,
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The surgeries in 1999 were conducted in Qinghai, Gansu, and
Hebei provinces, theGuangxi Zhuang Nationality Autonomous Region,
and the municipality of Tianjin and the 4,000 surgeries done in
2000 will be expanded into the provinces of Yunnan and Zhejiang
and will continue in Guangxi and Hebei, Baxter said.
</P>
<P>
The Smile Train is an international children's charity
committed to the eradication of cleft lips and palates. Through
partnerships with leading cleft organizations, medical
institutions and charitable associations, The Smile Train works to
improve the lives of millions of people around the world who are
born with cleft lips and palates.
</P>
<P>
The overall goal of The Smile Train is supported by three
primary initiatives: providing free surgeries for children who
would otherwise not receive medical treatment, training medical
professionals to enhance their proficiency in treating clefts, and
funding research to find causes of and cures for cleft lips and
palate anomalies.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other cleft organizations that rely on American
surgeons to perform surgery in foreign countries, The Smile Train
believes that local self-sufficiency is the only realistic, cost-
effective answer to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Throughout partnerships with a myriad of organizations that
are dedicated to helping children born with clefts, The Smile
Train helps to deliver smiles in 26 countries around the world,
including China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been supportive of this programme
and it is very successful in China, said the president of The
Smile Train.
</P>
<P>
In a historic visit to the United States in 1997, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin set aside time to discuss The Smile Train
with Charles B. Wang, chairman and chief executive officer of CA
and funding board member of The Smile Train. During their meeting,
President Jiang Zemin endorsed The Smile Train programme in China
and promised to support it.
</P>
<P>
The Smile Train has forged an effective partnership with the
China Charity Federation (CCF) to establish an infrastructure
through which safe and successful surgeries can be funded now and
in the future, said Bexter.
</P>
<P>
The CCF established an infrastructure within China through
which The Smile Train can fund surgeries. It assists in the
selection of medical institutions to perform safe and successful
surgeries and in managing the identification of surgical
candidates, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Smile Train will continue to train and update surgeons in
China and work with the Ministry of Health to take Chinese cleft
care to even the most remote areas of China, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Charles B. Wang is a founding director and one of the driving
forces behind The Smile Train, Bexter said.
</P>
<P>
Ever since he was first introduced to the miraculous and
immediate results of life-changing cleft surgery in 1994, Charles
has been a passionate, tireless and fervent supporter.
</P>
<P>
Beginning with his initial leadership gift of 10 million U.S.
dollars, Charles has helped raise millions for The Smile Train.
Along the way, he has enlisted the help of many of his friends,
including Chinese President Jiang Zemin, former U.S. President
George Bush, General Colin Powell, and Bill Gates, chairman and
chief executive officer of Microsoft Corporation.
</P>
<P>
As one of the world's most successful high-tech entrepreneurs,
Charles has a special interest in how computers and software can
help the problem of cleft. He has been actively involved in
developing The Smile Train virtual surgery project along the
innovative, interactive Cleft Curriculum Project.
</P>
<P>
"It used to be that all you could do with computers was create
spreadsheets and reports. Today, we can use them to create smiles.
There's nothing more powerful, more exciting, more rewarding than
using technology to change lives. Having the opportunity to help
give a little kid a new face and a new life is truly a blessing,"
Charles said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
