<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Prices In UK Likely To Fall In Shake-Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- British car buyers have over
recent years had to pay 10 to 12 percent more than those in France,
Germany and Italy for the same models.
</P>
<P>
Acting on a report by the Competition Commission, British Trade
and Industry Secretary Stephen Byers ordered manufacturers to
offer private purchasers the discounts normally available only to
fleet buyers.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that leading car companies had benefited from
a "complex monopoly situation." Together with Limitations
manufacturers imposed on their dealers, this led to higher prices
and was against the public interest.
</P>
<P>
Typically, consumer discounts average about 8 percent, while
fleet discounts range from about 17 to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Consumers Association welcomed Tuesday the findings as a
victory for its campaign against high UK car prices.
</P>
<P>
The association has long accused the UK motor industry of
operating as a monopoly and deliberately fixing new car prices.
</P>
<P>
The report found that the monopoly situation operated in favor
of 17 suppliers including Ford, Vauxhall and Rover, which together
accounted for 94 percent of new car registration in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Property Prices In Britain Cool Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The booming property market in
London and the South East appears to be cooling, according to the
latest quarterly figures from Halifax, the bank.
</P>
<P>
It said new figures showed the price of a typical London house
rose 4 percent in the first three months of this year -- less than
half the 8.5 percent growth notched up in the final quarter of
1999.
</P>
<P>
The overall rise in Britain property prices slowed in the first
three months of this year, up 3.2 percent compared with 3.6
percent in the last three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
But there were marked variations across the regions. Prices in
the West Middlands and the south-west rose 5.1 percent and 5
percent respectively over the period.
</P>
<P>
The housing market remained "buoyant" but the four interest
rate rises since September appeared to be having an impact on
demand, the Halifax said.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman from the bank said, "The favorable
economic and affordability background should maintain a robust
housing market during 2000." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
