<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Move Economy From Stability to Dynamism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Tuesday
outlined, in its economic guidelines for 2000, its aim of moving
the 15-nation bloc's economy from stability to dynamism.
</P>
<P>
The EU economy may enter a virtuous circle of vigorous output
growth, high confidence and strong job creation, said the
guidelines adopted Tuesday by the European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"An annual economic growth rate of around 3 percent for the EU
as a whole," stated the 45-page guidelines, "should be a realistic
prospect for the coming years."
</P>
<P>
The union Tuesday forecast an economic growth of 3.4 percent
for this year and a 3.1 percent increase for the next.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product growth rate for 2000 is forecast to
reach 3.4 percent for both the 15-nation European Union and the 11-
nation euro zone and the forecast is to be justified by strong
internal demand, recovery of exports, sound capital investment and
increased employment in the past year and this year, according to
Pedro Solbes Mira, EU economy commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The EU, however, has to cope well with the challenges in order
to materialize the guidelines. The challenges include the return
to full employment, the transition to a knowledge-based economy,
the impact of a rapidly aging population and the improvement of
social cohesion.
</P>
<P>
Solbes described the guidelines as a "key to coordination" as
the EU wanted the union's economy to move from stability to
dynamism.
</P>
<P>
The projection of economic growth of 3.4 percent this year and
3.1 percent next year is justified by growing internal demand,
recovery of exports, sound and strong capital investment and
recovering employment, said Solbes.
</P>
<P>
The union predicted an increase of around 3 percent in the
sector of private consumption and an increase of employment by 1.3
percent and of real wages by 1.1 percent. The increase of wages
will raise personal income and consumption sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The 3.4- and 3.1-percent growths have already been revised
according to the price hikes of the oil prices on the
international markets and the performance of inflation in the
union, according to the commissioner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
