<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Considers More Food Aid to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union said Tuesday
that it is considering sending this year another 150,000 tons of
food to Ethiopia to alleviate the drought-caused famine.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 70,000 tons will be provided to the non-
governmental organizations that are doing the relief in the
African country while 80,000 tons will be given to the World Food
Program.
</P>
<P>
Another 110,000 tons of food will be delivered at the beginning
of next year to the Ethiopian government for the replenishment of
the country's strategic food reserve.
</P>
<P>
Altogether the 15-nation European bloc will have furnished 432,
000 tons of food aid to Ethiopia in 2000 alone.
</P>
<P>
A first shipment of 30,000 tons of food aid has just arrived in
Djibouti. This followed a decision by the European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union, to allocate 60,000 tons of
food aid for Ethiopia to be distributed by European non-
governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The EU will be once more in the forefront of the international
community as donor of food aid to Ethiopia as it has continually
been in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The commission requested the Ethiopian authorities to fully
play its role in assuring the prompt and adequate distribution of
the food aid provided by the international community.
</P>
<P>
It strongly encouraged the Ethiopian government to find a rapid
and peaceful solution to its conflict with Eritrea that
considerably aggravated the food situation and seriously hampers
the relief efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
