<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Warmly Welcomed in Havana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Cuban leader Fidel Castro Tuesday
gave a red-carpet welcome to visiting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, who arrived here Monday night on the first visit to the
Caribbean Island country by a U.N. chief for nearly 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held at the Revolution Square, just outside
the Revolution Palace in Havana, where the two sides later held
talks.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who flew into Havana after his trips to Geneva, Rome
and Florence, paid an official visit to Cuba on April 11 and will
then attend the current South Summit of the Group of 77 (G-77) in
Havana on April 12-13.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Annan was greeted by Castro at the Havana
airport. The U.N. chief is scheduled to visit a university and a
historic center in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The last U.N. secretary-general to visit Cuba was Javier Perez
de Cuellar in May 1985.
</P>
<P>
Palestine leader Yasser Arafat, President Robert Mugabe of
Zimbabwe and President Cassam Uteem of Mauritius arrived in Havana
Monday night, and they were greeted by Jose Ramon Fernandez, vice
chairman of the Cuban Council of Ministers. They, together with
leaders from other African, Asian and Latin American countries,
are here to attend the South Summit, scheduled for April 10-14.
</P>
<P>
The current summit is the first ever summit and the largest
gathering in the history of the Group of 77, which, founded in
1964 by 77 developing countries, now has 133 members. It is the
largest Third World coalition in the United Nations and serves as
a focal point for the developing world to promote its collective
interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on
international economic issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
