<HEADLINE> France to Send Mission to U.N. on Lebanon Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- France will send a mission to the
United Nations headquarters in New York Wednesday to discuss the
question of Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon and the
consequent peacekeeping operation in the region.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry assistant spokesman Francois Rivasseau
said Tuesday that the delegation will be headed by Yves Aubin de
la Messuziere, director for African and Middle Affair affairs of
the Foreign Ministry, and Jean Felix-Paganon, director for U.N.
and international organizations affairs.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Defense Ministry will also join the
delegation, he said.
</P>
<P>
French officials will talk with U.N. officials on a possible
change of the role of the 4,500-man Intermediary Force for Lebanon
(UNIFL) deployed by the U.N. in Lebanon since 1978.
</P>
<P>
Israel says it will withdraw its troops from the 820 square-
kilometer security zone in southern Lebanon by July this year.
</P>
<P>
France, which participates in the UNIFL, has been asked by
Israel to deploy troops in the security zone. 
