<HEADLINE> Jordan Becomes WTO's 136th Member </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan becomes the 136th member of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) on April 11, the trade body
announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is truly a historical moment for Jordan, as we have long
aspired to become a member of the WTO," said R.M. Halaiqah, chief
negotiator and secretary general of the Ministry of Industry and
Trade of Jordan at the WTO's General Council meeting. "This is a
turning point in the continued development of the Jordanian
economy."
</P>
<P>
The WTO's General Council concluded negotiations with Jordan
and approved the accession package on December 17, 1999. Jordan
has agreed to assume all of its WTO obligations upon accession. In
addition, it has signed on to the two plurilateral agreements on
government procurement and on trade on civil aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the WTO's working party on Jordan K. Kesavapany of
Singapore noted that Jordan's accession was testimony to the fact
that the accession procedures under the WTO do work rapidly and
smoothly given the determination of acceding government to push
ahead and the cooperation and flexibility of members.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's main merchandise exports include phosphate and potash,
and chemicals. Jordan mainly imports transport equipment,
machinery and crude oil. Its major trading partners are other Arab
countries and the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP to Help China in Ozone Protection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 52-million U.S. dollar program will eliminate over 4,000
tons of ODS now being used by some 2,000 small and medium-sized
enterprises in China, and will help them substitute ozone-friendly
substances and identify energy efficient manufacturing processes,
according to a UNDP publication issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
ODS, such as aerosols and refrigerants, chemical solvents for
cleaning computer components and other electronic parts, pose
threats to the earth's ozone layer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
