<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Calls for Erase of Debt for Poor Countries  (Updated with Nigerian FM's statement) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo Tuesday said that rich countries should erase their debts
to the poor countries, which should not be paid at the cost of
economic and social development in the developing South.
</P>
<P>
The president, who is also chairman of the Group of 77 (G-77),
told a press conference here that the South cooperation is
essential to the decisions the developing countries take regarding
the globalization of world economy, access to technology and the
relations between the North and the South.
</P>
<P>
He also said that delegations to the South Summit, the largest
gathering of heads of state and government in the 36-year history
of G-77, are discussing the implementation of some kind of follow-
up mechanism for the agreement taken at the ministerial or summit
level.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo arrived in Havana, capital of Cuba which is the host
country of the G-77 summit, Monday. He is expected to chair the
summit, at which heads of state and government will meet for three
days beginning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian president said that if he goes to villagers and
tells them, "I wanted to give you water but I have to pay debts ...
even though the origin of these debts are dubious, and therefore I
will not be able to give you water ... they will say 'get away
with your new dispensation'," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he ruled out a joint decision by poor countries to
suspend debt payments, saying that it would interfere with aid
transfer that some nations depend upon for part of their domestic
budgets.
</P>
<P>
The statement by Obasanjo also coincided with the ideas in the
draft documents, which are expected to emerge from the South
Summit and call for giving poor countries a greater voice in
development decisions by encouraging the United Nations to play a
bigger role in economic aid, rather than channeling it through
organizations controlled by rich nations.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Alhaji Sule Lamido Monday told an
opening session of the meeting of foreign ministers that the
Havana Declaration, one of the final documents to be adopted at
the end of the South Summit on April 14, "will demonstrate to the
entire world our purpose and determination to promote and foster
cooperation among our countries."
</P>
<P>
The second final document -- the Program of Action, which, he
said, "we hope will include all of our priorities: South-South
cooperation, globalization of the economy and our relations with
the North."
</P>
<P>
The drafts also called on rich countries to give preferential
trade concessions to poorer nations and to liberalize rules on
movements of labor as they have with movement of capital.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77, set up by 77 developing countries, saw its
membership grow to 133 countries over the past three decades, but
its original name was retained due to its historic significance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
