<HEADLINE> Cyclone Causes 55 Million U.S. Dollars Damage in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The devastating floods caused by
ravaging Cyclone Eline in March have resulted in a damage of more
than 55 million U. S. dollars for Zimbabwe, a high-ranking
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Not only crops, roads, bridges and livestock were destroyed,
but also homes and lives were lost, said Local Government and
National Housing Minister John Nkome.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, 100 people were killed in the
country and more than 200,000 were left homeless in Masvingo,
Matabeleland and Manicaland provinces during the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Nkome said these figures were not conclusive because his
ministry, together with the affected organizations and
departments, was still doing a more analytical assessment.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is drafting a second domestic and international appeal
for donations, which would be released within the next month, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the reconstruction would be in three phases, starting
with the rebuilding of homes and opening access routes to
villages, schools and health facilities.
</P>
<P>
The short and long term phases would involve the rebuilding and
 repairing of roads and bridges, he added. 
</P>
