<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Dissolves Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Parliament of Zimbabwe will be
 dissolved with effect from midnight on Tuesday, President Robert
Mugabe announced in an extraordinary government gazette released
ahead of parliamentary general elections to be held next month.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is now in Cuba for G-77 Summit, made the
proclamation on April 8 under Subsection two of Section 63 of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
This section empowers the president to dissolve the parliament
at any time by a proclamation in the gazette.
</P>
<P>
The current Fourth Parliament is the last one before the 2000
general elections.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
(Zanu-pf) has been in power since the country attained its
independence in 1980. It faces a serious challenge from the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change which was formed last
year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that the composition of the House would be
changed soon after the elections as they foresee an increasing
number of members of the parliament from opposition political
parties.
</P>
<P>
The last 150-member chamber has only two members from the
opposition Zanu (Ndonga) party and one independent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
