<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Parliamentarians Call on People to Shun Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean parliamentarians
Tuesday urged people in the country to shun violence in the face
of the elections scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
Violence begot violence and Zimbabweans started to lose as a
people, said Member of the Parliament (MP) Mike Mataure.
</P>
<P>
"We should approach elections in a tolerant manner and compete
effectively," he said, urging people to have a tolerant attitude
towards those with different opinions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, MP Margaret Dongo said something had to be done to
curb the violence.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement agents should not be partisan, but be
professional in carrying out their duties, she said.
</P>
<P>
She suggested that all political leaders should have a special
conference to assess how to deal with the issue of political
violence which she said stemmed from selfish leaders who wanted to
further their aims.
</P>
<P>
MP Livingstone Manhombo said it was a great shame that as
Zimbabweans, even before they knew the actual date for elections,
began to unleash violence against each other.
</P>
<P>
"No Zimbabwean should encourage others to call for political
violence," he said, adding that "this is a time when police,
without fear or favour, should unleash all the powers invested in
them against perpetrators of violence."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 120 people have been arrested in
almost 100 cases of political violence, during which three people
were killed and 100 others injured. 
</P>
