<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Map Out Refugee Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government is
 committed to formulating a written refugee policy aimed at
tackling refugee management issues looming large in the country.
</P>
<P>
Officiating a three-day workshop on refugee law and policy held
here on Tuesday for decision-makers from Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania, Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Home Affairs
Bernard Mchomvu said the absence of such a policy is causing
misinterpretation of some stakeholders and interested parties over
refugee problems.
</P>
<P>
The refugee policy will be mapped out by next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Mchomvu, Tanzania does not have a written-down
refugee policy, but only a municipal law governing refugee matters
called the Refugees Act 1998.
</P>
<P>
The refugee influx is currently a big burden for Tanzania,
which alone hosts over 800,000 refugees from countries like
Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Rwanda and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
All prisons in the west regions of Tanzania are congested with
inmates as a result of increasing number of refugees jailed for
committing criminal offences.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over 26,000 refugees have been naturalized
since 1961.  
</P>
</TEXT>
