<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Straits Record 502 Accidents in 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Sea accidents totalling 502
occurred in the Turkish Straits in the past 50 years, killing 130
people, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total figure, 40 were defined as "big accidents,"
officials of the Chamber of Maritime Trade in Izmir, southeast
Turkey, were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the disasters, 386 took place in the Bosphorus Strait, 85
in Dardanelles Strait and the rest in the Sea of Marmara.
</P>
<P>
Turkey lies between Asia and Europe being surrounded by the sea
on three sides -- the Mediterranean in the south, the Aegean in the
west and the Black Sea in the north. The two continents are
separated by the Turkish Straits, consisting from southwest to
northeast, of the Dardanelles, the Sea of Marmara and the
Bosphorus.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that altogether 22,000 ships were destroyed
and thousands of tons of oil spilled into the sea, which caused
grave environment pollution.
</P>
<P>
As nearly 50,000 ships, including huge oil tankers, passed the
Turkish Straits every year in the half century, the officials
complained, Turkey could hardly do anything in connection with the
ships, which went through the straits in accordance with the
Montreux Convention (MONCON), signed in the Canadian city in 1936.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant MONCON provisions, commercial ships are entitled
to free passage through the waterway, with or without piloting,
regardless of their loads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
