<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes 10 Oil Tankers Smuggling Iraqi Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The patrol boats of the Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) of Iran seized 10 oil tankers
smuggling oil from Iraq on Monday and Tuesday, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The tankers, now anchored in the coast of an Iranian island,
were carrying a consignment of 45,000 tons of smuggled oil from
Iraq, said IRGC officer Isa Golverdi.
</P>
<P>
He said the tankers of different nationalities were involved in
smuggling oil and violating Iranian territorial waters, adding that
the documents of over 100 crew members on board the 10 tankers have
also been collected.
</P>
<P>
Tehran will not permit the use of Iranian territorial waters for
the smuggling of oil, the officer stressed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, which has been under crippling U.N. sanctions since its
1990 invasion of Kuwait, was banned from selling oil, its major
foreign currency earner, on world market.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. humanitarian oil-for-food program which took
effect in 1996 to ease the sufferings of the Iraqi ordinary people,
Iraq is allowed to sell oil only under the U.N. control, with the
proceeds used to fund humanitarian programs and the Gulf War
reparations.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its allies have repeatedly accused Baghdad
of smuggling refined oil out of its Basra and Abu Flus ports. And
Iran is also under fire for allowing smuggled Iraqi oil to pass
through its territory in return for kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, the IRGC have detained a Honduran-flagged
vessel and a tanker flying the Panamanian flag for allegedly trying
to smuggle Iraqi oil in violation of the U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Urges Trade-Law Harmonization in E. Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew Tuesday stressed the need for East Asian countries to
develop a congruence between laws and rules governing trade and
investment so as to ensure stability, predictability and low
transaction costs in economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Millennium Law Conference gala dinner hosted by
Singapore Academy of Law, Lee said, "To maximize growth potential,
East Asian countries need to harmonize those parts of their legal
systems that concern cross-border trade."
</P>
<P>
He said this is especially important in view of the fact that
East Asian countries are at different levels of economic
development and do not have similar political systems, historical
origins and common legal roots.
</P>
<P>
"There is a fundamental need for the rule of law. It ensures
stability and predictability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee added that the ASEAN Free Trade Area and the ASEAN
Investment Area can be a possible vehicle for this process of
harmonization and the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation can also
play a role in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"These regional groupings can promote the adoption of
international standards which will facilitate the integration of
economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the World Trade Organization (WTO), which suffered
a setback at its ministerial meeting in Seattle last November, Lee
said, "WTO obligations, together with compulsory dispute
resolution mechanisms, must be the way ahead." "Its emphasis on
upholding agreed rules and regulations will ensure that the rule
of law will be established for international transactions and the
international trading system will be more secure and predictable."
</P>
<P>
The three-day Singapore Law Conference with the theme of "
leading the law and lawyers into the new millennium" is attended
by some 500 people including more than 80 foreign delegates from
19 countries or areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
