<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa Urges IMF not to Ignore Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa said on Tuesday
it will press for greater say for the developing countries in the
decision-making of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
South African Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said in Cape Town
before he left for Washington for the spring meetings of the IMF
and the World Bank that he was particularly concerned about the
dominance of the United States and Europe Union in the
decision-making in the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The structure and operations of the IMF and the World Bank are
unsuited to the global economy in the year 2000. The poor
countries are completely ignored, it is wrong for this very cosy
agreement to exclude the majority of the world's people," he said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa will continue to campaign for the write-off of
some poor countries' debt at the meeting, Manuel added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
