<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Foreign Ministers Hold Preparatory Meeting for South Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the Group
of 77 countries met Tuesday here to prepare for the next day's
South Summit, the largest gathering of heads of state and
government since the founding of the body in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from 133 G-77 member states are also expected
to ponder over the two final draft documents -- the Declaration
and the Program of Action, which will collectively address the
negative impact of globalization on developing countries, the
current unjust international economic system, and poorer nations'
heavy debt burden.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was launched by Nigerian Foreign Minister Alhaji
Sule Lamido, whose country holds the G-77 chairmanship for the
year 2000. He said that the Summit will focus on globalization,
knowledge and technology, the South-South cooperation, and the
North-South relations.
</P>
<P>
Delivering welcoming statement at the opening session, Cuban
Foreign Minister Felipe Perez Rouqe said the time has come for the
Third World countries to work hard to help people out of
starvation and stand up to the challenge imposed by the current
unjust international economic system.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers are here to attend the South Summit,
scheduled for April 10-14, together with their respective head of
state or government. They will discuss the role of the United
Nations in the 21st century on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Working meetings of senior officials began in the morning and
lasted into late Monday night. Talks by heads of state are to take
place Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This summit will give a new emphasis on cooperation among
ourselves," the Cuban foreign minister said, adding that the South-
South cooperation cannot make progress without the North.
</P>
<P>
G-77 was founded on June 15, 1964 by 77 developing countries in
Geneva. Although its current membership has increased to 133
countries, the original name was retained because of its historic
significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations and
the largest grouping in the South, the organization provides means
for the developing world to articulate and promote its collective
economic interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on
all major international economic issues in the United Nations
system, and promote economic and technical cooperation among
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
