<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- U.S. employers can fill less than half of the
information technology jobs available next year, indicating that
the country is ill-equipped to staff the source of its economic
growth, according to an industry group study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Information Technology Association of America (ITAA)
determined in its study that IT work force in the United States
numbers over 10 million and needs 1.6 million more workers in 2000.
Hiring managers foresee a shortfall of almost 850,000
appropriately skilled workers. (U.S.-IT-Jobs)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- An Iranian official on Tuesday underlined the urgency
of Iran's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO), calling
it an "inevitable necessity."
</P>
<P>
Sooner or later Iran should join the WTO, and any delay in
joining the world organization will create problems for the
country's production units, said Hussein Naji, deputy industries
minister for non-ferrous industries. (Iran-WTO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Ugandan police have announced a reward of 12 million
shillings (8,000 U.S. dollars) to those who will provide
information leading to the arrest of the six main leaders of the
cult Movement for the Restoration of the Ten Commandments of God,
the Monitor newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Police Spokesman Asuman Mugenyi as saying
that they had put up a reward of two million shillings (1,333 U.S.
dollars) to anybody who gives a clue leading to the arrest of
each of the six cult leaders including Joseph Kibwetere, founder
of the cult organization.  (Uganda-Cult)
</P>
