<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Forecasts 3.4 Percent Economic Growth for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Tuesday forecast an economic growth of 3.4 percent for this year
and 3.1 percent for next year.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the gross domestic product for 2000 is estimated
at 3.4 percent for both the 15-nation EU and the 11-nation euro
zone, according to the forecast.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was justified by strong internal demand, recovery
of exports, sound capital investment and increased employment in
the past year and this year, said Pedro Solbes Mira, EU economy
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Though not as strong as the increase in the United States, the
EU experienced strong growth of its own, Solbes said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of last year was 2.3 percent, with the fourth
quarter witnessing 0.8 percent and 0.9 percent of growth in the EU
and the euro zone respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's forecast projected an increase of around 3 percent in
the sector of private consumption, a 1.3-percent rise in
employment and a 1.1-percent increase in real wages.
</P>
<P>
The increase of wages will raise personal income and
consumption sentiment, according to Solbes.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference televised live to Brussels from
Strasbourg that in the three-year period from 1999 to 2001, a
total of 6 million jobs will be created to ride the economic
growth thrust.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment will go down to a level not seen since the
recession years in 1992 and 1993," said Solbes, who briefed the
European Parliament about the economic forecast and the general
guidelines of the economic policies of the EU and its member
states.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate for both the EU and the euro zone is now
just below 10 percent and with the new forecast, the jobless rate
is expected to drop to near 8 percent within two years, he added.
</P>
<P>
Solbes said that both the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development and the International Monetary Fund gave lower
forecast for the year 2001 than that for 2000 and the development
elsewhere will exert influence on the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
