<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish NGO Calls for More Aid to Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Finland's non-governmental
Service Center for Development Cooperation on Monday urged Finnish
parliament to increase aid to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Jorma Kukkonen, chief of the organization, made the appeal in
an article published in Helsingin Sanomat (Helsinki News), the
largest newspaper in Finland.
</P>
<P>
He said the gravest human right problem is poverty currently
prevalent in the Third World, urging the developed countries to
increase their assistance to the developing world.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the assistance in the 1980s, aid programs today
are mostly well-planned but ill-financed, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Finnish government has failed to
provide the aid it has promised accounting for 0.4 percent of its
GDP to help the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Kukkonen urged the Finnish parliament to allocate at least 0.34
percent of the country's GDP to meet the so-called "face-saving
bottom line," and to increase the percentage of development aid in
its GDP to 0.7 percent by 2010 to meet the UN requirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
