<HEADLINE> Nobel Laureate Optimistic About China's Scientific Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Nobel Laureate Chen Ning Yang
said in a lecture to government officials and local scholars in
Yunnan Province today that he is optimistic about China's
scientific development in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In his lecture titled "Chinese Culture and Science," Chen
recapped China's scientific accomplishments over the past century.
</P>
<P>
Following his talk, Chen, the recipient of the 1957 Nobel Prize
for physics, accepted an offer from Yunnan provincial government
to serve as a government consultant.
</P>
<P>
"In 1900, no Chinese knew about calculus, which already became
a course for a freshman in western universities," said Chen,
adding that China succeeded in launching its first experimental
spacecraft, the Shenzhou, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a review of China's past 100 years of scientific
development shows the country has made remarkable progress.
</P>
<P>
"During the past 100 years, China has achieved the same
scientific development seen in western countries in the past 700
years," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Chen pointed out that China possesses the three elements
necessary for scientific development in the coming century:
talented personnel, resolve, and economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
