<HEADLINE> Mitsubishi Chemicals Plant Inaugurated in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's industrial giant
Mitsubishi Chemicals Corporation Tuesday inaugurated a major
purified terephthalic acid (PTA) plant in Haldia city of Northeast
India's West Bengal state, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 16 billion rupees (372 million U.S.
dollars), the plant is capable of producing 350,000 tons of PTA
each year, which can be used for manufacturing polyester staple
fiber, polyester filament yarn, bottle and industrial grade
polyester resins and polyester chips, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural function, Japanese Ambassador to
India Hiroshi Hirabayashi said Japanese-Indian relations would be
strengthened through this project.
</P>
<P>
Indian Fertilizer and Chemicals Minister Suresh Prabhu noted
that the inauguration of the plant had opened the door to
industrial development in eastern India.
</P>
<P>
West Bengal Chief Minister Jyoti Basu said at the inaugural
ceremony that his state government would take steps to ensure
increased private participation and transform Haldia into a modern
township.
</P>
<P>
The West Bengal government will set up growth centers to
attract private entrepreneurs and a task force has already been
set up for the purpose, he said. 
</P>
