<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Demolish Unauthorized Tollhouses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Home, Post and
Telecommunications Minister Mohammad Nasim Tuesday said a
demolition drive will begin on Wednesday to remove unauthorized
toll collection houses on roads and highways across the country.
</P>
<P>
Deputy commissioners and superintendents of police have been
asked to demolish the illegal tollhouses on roads and highways
under their respective jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The deadline set by the government for removing all illegal
tollhouses ended Tuesday, the minister told a press briefing at
his office.
</P>
<P>
He said police and Bangladesh Rifles would be on roads and
highways from Wednesday to help the demolition process. Those
involved in illegal toll collection in the name of welfare of
transport workers would be arrested under Public Safety Act, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Nasim said that only toll collection permitted by the
government is valid for the maintenance of bridges or any
government establishments. The demolition drive will continue till
all illegal tollhouses are removed from roads and highways.
</P>
<P>
The minister said illegal toll collection has reached such a
dimension that bus terminals are now known as crime zones. The so-
called labor organizations and toll collectors who build up their
fortunes overnight are doing the business of smuggling drug and
illegal arms, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
