<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Form Civilian Crisis Management Instrument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Tuesday proposed setting up a civilian crisis management arm to
enable swift mobilization of police, customs officers, judges and
other non-military personnel for conflict prevention.
</P>
<P>
A Rapid Reaction Facility (RRF) should be established to
enhance the bloc's civilian capacity to intervene swiftly and
effectively in crisis points outside the union, proposed the
commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Patten, EU commissioner for external relations,
said, "The creation of a Rapid Reaction Facility will allow us to
mobilize our resources within hours or days rather than weeks or
months."
</P>
<P>
"This is one of the main lessons learned from the experiences
the international community made in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Kosovo and
East Timor," he added.
</P>
<P>
The RRF will operate through a separate budget line reinforced
by the authority of the commission to decide quickly on urgent
interventions of up to 5 million euros (4.8 million U.S. dollars)
and each intervention will have a cost ceiling of 12 million euros
(11.5 million dollars) and a time limit of nine months.
</P>
<P>
The European Council summit in Helsinki last December called on
the commission to set up a civilian crisis management facility,
with the aim to accelerate the provision of finance to support EU
activities worldwide, to contribute to operations run by
international organizations and to fund non-governmental
organization activities.
</P>
<P>
The added value of the RRF is its speed and flexibility in
situations of high tension immediately prior to, during and after
crises, according to officials from the commission.
</P>
<P>
The activities of the RRF range from alleviation of financial
burdens, human rights work, election monitoring, institution
building, media support, border management, humanitarian missions,
mine-clearing  operations, police training and the provision of
police equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
