<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders Arrive in Havana for South Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Cuban leader Fidel Castro will
chair an official ceremony Tuesday morning to welcome United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan as leaders of member states
of the Group of 77 developing countries arrived in the Cuban
capital for the group's South Summit.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here Monday night, is the first U.N. chief
to visit the Caribbean island country since 1985 when the then U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar visited the country.
</P>
<P>
Annan is among leaders from worldwide to attend the largest
gathering of heads of state and government since the founding of
the group in June 1964. G-77 is the largest Third World coalition
in the world.
</P>
<P>
The summit will focus on the impact of globalization and the
heavy debt burden of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Current G-77 chairman, Arthur Mbanefo, who is also Nigeria's
permanent representative to the U.N., told a press conference here
Monday afternoon that the summit would seek ways to help poorer
nations merge into an increasingly wired world of Internet
information to face the challenge of globalization at the turn of
century.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 also implied that the group may urge developed
countries to relieve poorer nations' debt burden. "We would like
to see a situation where some of this debt is canceled," he said,
adding some countries spend twice as much servicing their debt as
they do on social services.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from 133 G-77 member states are to meet at
the Havana International Conference Center Tuesday morning. Senior
officials began working meeting Monday to hammer out the final
documents which will emerge from the Summit, which is scheduled to
conclude on April 14. Heads of state and government will meet on
Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We tend to use the South Summit as an opportunity to
revitalize the South-South cooperation so as to face the challenge
of globalization," Mbanefo said.
</P>
<P>
The Summit is "unmistakable proof that our countries want our
voice to be heard, and that the interests of our countries, which
are the majority, are taken into account," Cuban Foreign Minister
Felipe Perez Roque said at a press conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
By Monday, 122 member countries have sent delegations, as had
34 nonmember countries and 35 international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, headed by Vice Premier Li Lanqing, is
scheduled to arrive here on Tuesday afternoon. China has long been
in close ties with G-77, and the Cuban foreign minister spoke
highly of China's support for the group.
</P>
<P>
Although the group, founded by 77 developing countries on June
15, 1964 in Geneva, saw its membership grown to 133 countries, the
original name was retained because of its historic significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest grouping in the South, G-77 provides the means
for the developing world to articulate and promote its collective
economic interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on
all major international economic issues in the United Nations
system, and promote economic and technical cooperation among
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
