<HEADLINE> Tokyo Governor Criticized For Anti-Foreigner Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Japanese government
and opposition parties on Tuesday blasted Tokyo Governor Shintaro
Ishihara for his recent discriminative remarks against foreigners
living in Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Atrocious crimes have been committed again and again by
sangokujin (people from Taiwan or Korea or their descendants) and
other foreigners. We can expect them to riot in the event of a
disastrous earthquake," Ishihara said Sunday while addressing
members of Japan's Ground Self-Defense Force (GSDF).
</P>
<P>
Ishihara also called on the GSDF to control the possible
rioting by foreigners following a major earthquake.
</P>
<P>
"There may be people who have perceived that their honor has
been stained by that word," Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono
said when referring to Ishihara's use of the word "sangokujin."
</P>
<P>
"I believe we should not use the word carelessly," Kono told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
At a separate news conference, Japanese Defense Agency Director-
General Tsutomu Kawara flatly dismissed Ishihara's views on the
possibility of rioting by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly, I don't believe that would happen," Kawara said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leaders of the Japanese opposition parties strongly
criticized Ishihara for his remarks.
</P>
<P>
"It's an absurd comment and must not be forgiven. I feel fierce
indignation," said Yukio Hatoyama, leader of the Democratic Party
of Japan (DPJ).
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Party (SDP), in a statement, urged
Ishihara to apologize for the comment.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara "made the comment to encourage racial discrimination
on purpose. It must not be overlooked. We want him to immediately
withdraw the comment and apologize," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Sankokujin," a Japanese term that literally means "people from
third- world countries," gained currency after World War II. It is
now widely regarded as a derogatory term which refers to people
from former Japanese colonies in Taiwan and the Korean peninsula
as well as their descendants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
