<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Posts First Rise in 13 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus in
February surged 33.3 percent from a year earlier to 1,473.7
billion yen (13.5 billion U.S. dollars), registering the first
rise in 13 months, the Finance Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge in the current account surplus came as a climb in
exports outweighed an increase in imports, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Exports jumped 13.9 percent to 3,948.0 billion yen (36.1
billion dollars) while imports grew 11.4 percent to 2,646.9
billion yen (24.2 billion dollars), both marking the fourth
straight month of expansion.
</P>
<P>
Japan's shipment to the United States, the 15-member European
Union and other Asian countries increased 10.8 percent, 3.2
percent and 32.1 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in goods and services trade totaled 947.0 billion
yen (8.7 billion dollars), soaring 54.6 percent for the first rise
in eight months.
</P>
<P>
The merchandise trade surplus increased 19.4 percent to 1,301.1
billion yen (11.9 billion dollars), while the services deficit
contracted to 354.1 billion yen (3.2 billion dollars) due to
scaled-back deficits in the payment of patent royalties.
</P>
<P>
The yen averaged 109.34 against the dollar in February,
compared with a rate of 116.66 yen to the U.S. dollar a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance represents the difference between a
nation's income from foreign sources and foreign obligations
payable, excluding net capital investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
