<HEADLINE> Russian Supreme Court Annuls Decree Against Moscow Police Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Supreme Court on Tuesday
annulled a December 1999 decree by the former President Boris
Yeltsin to fire the then Moscow police chief Nikolai Kulikov.
</P>
<P>
The appeal board of the Court decided to do away with an
earlier Supreme Court rejection of a complaint by Moscow Mayor
Yuri Luzhkov, which declared Yeltsin's degree "illegal."
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov had argued that Nikolai Kulikov's dismissal as head of
Moscow's Chief Interior Administrator ran against the Russian
Constitution, Moscow's local law and the law on the police, which
forbid national authorities to appoint or dismiss city police
chief without the consent of the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
He said Kulikov had been appointed deputy interior minister to
"raise the status of the largest and most complicated regional
interior administration." 
