<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Define 5 "NOs" in Washington Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian team has defined
five "Nos" in their ongoing negotiations with the Israeli side in
the United States Bolling Air Base near Washington, a Palestinian
source close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Arabic daily Al-Aiyam, the source said the five "
NOs" are as follows:
</P>
<P>
- No for giving up any part of the Palestinian territories
seized (by Israel) in the l967 Middle East war, including
Jerusalem;
</P>
<P>
- No for accepting settlement legitimacy;
</P>
<P>
- No for delaying discussions on such issues as Jerusalem and
refugees and for accepting a partial framework agreement;
</P>
<P>
- No for any kind of Israeli military presence inside the
(future) Palestinian State territories from Jordan river border to
joint border with Egypt;
</P>
<P>
- No for the policy of repatriating Palestinian refugees in
places other than their homeland.
</P>
<P>
The talks in Washington between Israel and the Palestinians are
aimed to conclude a framework agreement by May to pave the way for
a final peace treaty by September 2000 as well as pushing the
Israeli side to go ahead with the army redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The talks entered into the fourth day on Monday, the source
claimed, adding that there was a session on the framework
agreement, followed by a trilateral meeting with U.S. Middle East
peace envoy Denis Ross who then attended a long discussion on the
last phase of Israeli army redeployment.
</P>
<P>
About 43 percent of the West Bank has already been under partial
and full Palestinian authority.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli government stressed that it will not drop
its own four "NOs" with regard to giving up Jerusalem or dividing
it, dismantling big settlements, return of Palestinian refugees, or
the return to pre-l967 Mideast War borders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak arrives in
Washington on Tuesday for talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on
the Palestinian track of the peace process ahead of a visit to the
U.S. capital by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on April 20 for
the same purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
