<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Launch First Vehicle Tracking System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- India's first satellite-based
vehicle tracking system will be launched in the southern city of
Bangalore next week to monitor local buses, the Press Trust of
India (PTI) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The system, developed by Bharat Electronics Ltd. (BEL) of India,
will help determine the exact distance covered by buses, prevent
traffic violations by these vehicles and determine their arrival
time at a particular stop, said the PTI.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the system will also enable Bangalore
Metropolitan Transport Corporation to make correct payments to bus
owners who collect money according to the distance their vehicles
run in the service, the PTI added.
</P>
<P>
The system, whose development was funded by India's Ministry of
Information Technology, relies on the global positioning system (
GPS) for vehicle monitoring, H. Seshadri Sekhar, manager of the
BEL, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A GPS receiver, mounted on the vehicle, continuously acquires
position data through the GPS satellites and the data will be
stored on a computer at the control station, said Sekhar.
</P>
<P>
Subsequently, the data will be downloaded to a geographical
information system, a computerized navigational system, to
determine the distance travelled by a bus and traffic violations,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
