<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most S. Koreans Support Inter-Korean Summit: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The majority of South Koreans
support the inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang scheduled for June 12-
14, according to a poll conducted by the Korea Information Service
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of the 1,000 people over the age of 20 polled
supported the forthcoming summit, which will be the first since
the Korean peninsula was divided in 1945.
</P>
<P>
A total of 51 percent said they support the summit, 38 percent
said they "strongly" back it, while 8 percent are opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
Some 82 percent favored the engagement policy toward the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and 62 percent
expected progress in inter-Korean relations.
</P>
<P>
On the priority topics at the summit, 48 percent said the
reunion of separated families is the most important, 20 percent
preferred economic cooperation, 17 percent wanted to end the Cold
War on the peninsula and build mutual confidence, and 7 percent
expected establishment of personal relations and cultural
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Some 68 percent said that the summit will help influence
Pyongyang's attitude to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and the DPRK reached an agreement in China on April
8 to hold a summit in Pyongyang in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
