<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung Expects Summit to Materialize Berlin Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
said Tuesday that he will discuss economic cooperation and reunion
of separated families with Kim Jung-il, leader of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), at the forthcoming summit.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet meeting, Kim Dae-jung said he will uphold the
spirit of the South-North Joint Communique signed on July 4, 1972,
and the 1991 South-North Basic Agreement at the inter-Korean
summit, which will be held in Pyongyang on June 12-14 this year
under an agreement reached by the two sides in China early this
month.
</P>
<P>
"Among others, I will make efforts to materialize the four
proposals that I made in Berlin," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
In Berlin on March 8 during his European trip, Kim proposed
that Seoul and Pyongyang reconcile to end the Cold War on the
Korean peninsula, conduct economic cooperation and inter-
government dialogue, allow reunions of separated families and
exchange special envoys to carry out the South-North Basic
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will offer both humanitarian and economic aid to
the DPRK to help reconstruct the DPRK's infrastructure, Kim said.
</P>
<P>
"The economic cooperation will take the form of investment and
loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kim also said restoring mutual confidence is the most urgent
task facing the two sides, urging both the government and private
sector to join forces to solve inter-Korean issues.
</P>
<P>
He instructed his ministers to take all necessary measures to
prepare for the summit, which will be the first-ever since the
peninsula was divided in 1945.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kim called on the South Korean political circle to
support the inter-Korean summit on a nonpartisan basis.
</P>
<P>
"The most proud thing in agreeing to the summit meeting is that
we discussed and reached an agreement on the national issues by
ourselves," added the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
