<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Grouse Confirmed Extinct in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have confirmed
that a rare kind of grouse living in frigid zones is extinct in
China.
</P>
<P>
The extinct spruce grouse, belonging to the species of
ptarmigan, only inhabits coniferous forests in frigid zones.
</P>
<P>
During a five-year investigation, researchers searched all the
possible habitats in China of spruce grouse but found none, said
Yu Xiaolian, an expert with the Heilongjiang Research Institute of
Wild Life.
</P>
<P>
No one in China has sighted the bird in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"According to articles from the Red List Categories of
International Union for the Conservation of Nature, the bird is
extinct in China," said Yu.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the bird mainly live in southeastern part of
Siberia in Russia and northeastern part of China.
</P>
<P>
Yu attributes the extinction of the bird to fewer coniferous
forests.
</P>
<P>
Jia Jingbo, professor from Northeast China Forestry University,
said that wildlife remains a critical issue despite efforts from
the Chinese government to protect wildlife. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
