<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Names 33 Ecological Demonstration Counties, Prefectures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-three countries and
prefectures across China were named today as ecological
demonstration areas by the State Environmental Protection
Administration of China (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
The areas, including Yanqing County in northern Beijing, are
the first in China to have met the economic, social, and
environmental requirements of China's sustainable development
strategy.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Guangyao, deputy director of the SEPA, said the 33 areas
were carefully chosen from 154 pilot areas, and will serve as good
examples of coordinated social, economic, and environmental
development.
</P>
<P>
Construction of ecological demonstration areas will remain an
important part of improving regional ecological conditions and an
effective way toward sustained economic and social development at
regional levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
The environmental requirements contain 19 specific development
targets, including the forest coverage rate, the consumption rate
of environment-friendly energy, and reduction in consumption of
farm chemicals and chemical fertilizers, as well as the quality of
air and water and the use of recycled solid waste.
</P>
<P>
China planned in 1995 to set up 50 ecological demonstration
counties and prefectures by the end of 2000 as part of its efforts
to curb the deterioration of the environment.
</P>
<P>
Many more of China's 2,000 counties and prefectures are
expected to meet these standards in the years ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Issue Biannual Land Resources Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China will issue a biannual
report on land use and forecast land resources in the future,
according to the Ministry of Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
The report will be based on local investigation on land use
including the change of arable land areas and returning farmland
to forest and grasslands.
</P>
<P>
The first report will come out by the middle of the year on
changes in China's land resources from November 1999 to April this
year. It will become a periodical biannual report, said an
official of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
China has the third largest land area in the world, but its per-
capita cultivated land is only 0.1 hectare, or 43 percent of the
world's average.
</P>
<P>
The revised Land Use Law, considered as the strictest in the
world, went into effect in 1999, aiming to protect and rationally
develop the natural resources, and keep coordinated development
between social economy, natural resources and environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
