<HEADLINE> Iranian Minister Calls for Adherence to Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Interior Minister Abdolvahed
Mousavi Lari on Tuesday called on political factions in the country
to observe the constitution while expressing their views and
engaging in political activities.
</P>
<P>
Only those who have accepted the constitution have the right to
be politically active, to express their views and to participate in
various activities to decide the fate of the nation, Lari was
quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Admitting each group has its own remedy to cure problems facing
the society, the minister urged political parties in the country to
be tolerant to different views and positions and adhere to the
constitution, which is the common accord of the people.
</P>
<P>
Tolerance of views will contribute toward progress of society
whereas intolerance will lead to tension and undermine national
security, he said.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the recent "illegal acts" by certain groups, which
included the assassination attempt against Saeed Hajjarian, deputy
chairman of Tehran municipal council.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, a vanguard in the country's reformist campaign, was
severely wounded by a shot in the face last month. So far 10
suspects related to the case have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Lari, whose ministry supports the reformist trend in the
country, made the statement amid tension of political struggles in
the country following sensitive parliamentary elections in
February.
</P>
<P>
Reformers supporting Iranian President Mohammed Khatami won an
overwhelming victory in the elections, dealing a severe blow to the
powerful conservatives.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Lari also expressed his concern about the
annulment of certain election results by the Council of Guardians
that supervises the elections. The council's act has stirred up a
series of protests in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
