<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan's oil output rose 33 percent to hit 200,000
barrels per day (bpd) in the last six months and its total oil
exports were lifted by 20 percent during the period.
</P>
<P>
The local daily al-Ra'i quoted major Nile Firm officials as
saying that many foreign companies have offered to explore crude
oil in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
A refinery at capacity of 450,000 bpd will set into work in
Khartoum as of April 15.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states spent about 35
billion U.S. dollars, or over one third of their total
expenditures, on arms and military equipment purchases in l998,
according to the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily al-Alam al-Youm quoted the Unified Arab
Economic Report as saying that from 1992 to 1998, the six GCC
members spent more than 160 billion dollars, about one fourth of
their 650-billion-dollar spending, on military purposes.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Iran on Monday reiterated that it will not give up its
oil quota though it did not participate in the recent agreement on
output increase by members of the Organization of Petrol Exporting
Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Al-Alam al-Youm quoted Iran's envoy to the OPEC Governor
Council, Hussein Kasimbur Ardabili, as saying that Iran will not
increase its supplies in the market.
</P>
<P>
Last month, nine OPEC states decided to raise daily output by 1.
45 million barrels to quench the surging price. Iran, which pressed
for a minimum increase, did not take part in the decision.
</P>
<P>
Under the recent deal, Iran should move up its daily output to
3.623 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt exported 50 million dollars worth of cast-iron
pipes and valves to the United Arab Emirates' water and sewerage
projects.
</P>
<P>
Nasir Casting Company Chairman Usama Abd el-Wahab said his firm
received another 40-million-dollar offer to export similar amounts
of made-in-Egypt pipes to be used in several other UAE areas.
</P>
<P>
Egypt exported 15 million dollars worth of pipes to Syria, he
said, adding that the company will bid into a 19-million-dollar
international tender to export such type of pipes to Oman.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia also offered to import the Egyptian-made pipes, he
said, pointing that the offer is under examination at present.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey plans to invite purchasing delegations from
approximately 150 foreign companies to visit Turkey this year,
reported Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the visit sponsored by the Foreign Trade
Undersecretariat, the importers will participate in various sectors
fairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey will host trade delegations from Saudi Arabia,
Syria and Iran in May, South Korea and China's Taiwan in November.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will set up its first National Cotton Council
in this year's cotton season, reported Turkish Daily News on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The council will be responsible for forming a national cotton
policy and supporting farmers in producing better-quality and
cheaper cotton. It will gather information about the rate of cotton
exports, Turkey's cotton producing capacity and world cotton prices
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at a meeting Monday organized by
Turkish Agriculture Sales Cooperatives and some other institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
