<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres Urges Peace Talks With Syria Under U.N. Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Syrian peace talks
should be conducted in line with with the relevant United Nations
resolutions, and only in this way can the two sides settle the
issue of the Golan Heights, said a senior Israeli official Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres made the remarks to
Israel Radio, just before Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.
S. President Bill Clinton are scheduled to hold their summit
meeting at the White House in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338 call on, among other things,
the negotiating parties in the Middle East to settle their
territorial disputes under the principle of "land for peace."
</P>
<P>
Peres expressed his welcome to the Washington summit between
Barak and Clinton, but said it will be difficult for the two
leaders to decide on the resumption of the Israeli-Syrian talks as
the Syrian side has not changed its positions.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks were stalled in January after the
two sides held two rounds of talks in the United States since its
resumption last December, as Israel refused to return to Syria the
entire Golan Heights which Israel occupied during the 1967 Middle
East War.
</P>
<P>
To rescue the peace talks will be one of the topics that Barak
and Clinton will discuss during their summit.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks are to resolve four main issues,
namely the border, security arrangement, water and normalization of
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the last two rounds of talks, the Israeli side wanted to
discuss and settle the security arrangement and normalization of
ties first, while the Syrians put the border issue on the top of
the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Syria also said that Israel must withdraw from the Golan Heights
to the June 4, 1967 lines, otherwise, there will be no need for the
two sides to continue the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
