<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is
committed to maintaining law and order by taking tough measures
against anti-social and harmful aspects such as terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala said at the annual
conference of senior police officers here Monday that effective
and united actions would be taken in the near future against the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Nepali Police would be mobilized to combat
terrorism and other related measures would also be initiated
against the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The police force will bear the big responsibility of dealing
with issues of the ultra-leftist guerrillas and other criminal
activities facing the country, Koirala said.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the participants of the conference to face the
challenges of terrorism with a high morale and professional
resolve and bring law and order to the country.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister issued an order on the occasion to make the
Special Police Department more dynamic and effective in combating
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Home Minister Govind Raj Joshi said the
government will soon form an armed security force which may take a
para-military form to focus on combating the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The ultra-leftist guerrillas have been engaged in violent
activities since 1996. About 1,300 people, including police,
guerrillas and civilians, have been killed in clashes between
guerrillas and police.
