<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angola Plays Down Dispute with Portugal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Bian Zhuodan
</P>
<P>
LUANDA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Angolan officials are making
effort to play down the dispute with its former colonial power
Portugal over the entry visas, with an Angolan official describing
it as "storm in a tea cup".
</P>
<P>
After Portugal's strong reaction to the Angolan rejection of
the entry of 27 Portuguese citizens to the southwest African
country, the Angolan Interior Ministry made a clarification on the
incidents which took place respectively last Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued by the Interior Ministry,
those Portuguese citizens, who arrived in Angola by the flights of
Air Portugal, were impeded from entering Angola mainly due to the
lack of working permits for those Portuguese who wanted to enter
Angola with tourist visas and then work in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an Angolan diplomat said in an international meeting
of the Portuguese-speaking countries that the relations between
Angola and Portugal are "excellent".
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said on Monday that
he would respond firmly to any unjustified alteration of the
Angolan policy on the Portuguese visitors, local informed sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Guterres promised to "act with total firmness" if Luanda's
attitude is found "not to correspond to the good state of
relations between Angola and Portugal".
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama, acting on instructions
from Guterres, said on Monday that he had asked Portuguese
embassy in Luanda " to insist on clarification" of the incidents,
which he described as " unprecedented" and "disagreeable".
</P>
<P>
Angolan officials stressed the legality of the airport
procedures, while emphasizing that the government may take steps
to avoid repeated situations.
</P>
<P>
 Local analysts noted that the incidents came after the recent
 bilateral tensions triggered by the former Portuguese President
Mario Soares, who publicly denounced "corruption" and
"dictatorial" practices in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Some Angolan officials accused Soares, now a socialist member
of the European Parliament, of benefiting from illegal diamond
trade by the Angolan rebels led by Jonas Savimbi. 
</P>
