<HEADLINE> British Historian Loses Holocaust Libel Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- British historian David Irving,
who denies that Hitler masterminded mass slaughters and calls the
Auschwitz death camp a Disneyland built after war, Tuesday lost
his High Court libel action against a U.S. professor and her
publishers.
</P>
<P>
Irving, 62, had sued Penguin Books, a subsidiary of media giant
Pearson Plc, and professor Deborah Lipstadt of Emory University in
Atlanta, Georgia, over a book written in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The book said Irving was a partisan of Adolf Hitler, a
holocaust denier and a falsifier of history.
</P>
<P>
Irving said the book destroyed his livelihood and generated
waves of hatred against him.
</P>
<P>
The court judged that what the book says are substantially true
and Irving did have for his own ideological reasons persistently
and deliberately misrepresented and manipulated historical
evidence.
</P>
<P>
Irving has been banned from going to Germany after a 1992
conviction for denying the Holocaust and has also been refused
entry to Canada, Italy, Austria and Australia.
</P>
<P>
He said he will not appeal against the verdict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
