<HEADLINE> China Issues Gold Millennium Commemorative Coins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
issued a set of gold and silver millennium commemorative coins
today.
</P>
<P>
One set consists of four gold and three silver coins, and all
are legal Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
The obverse sides of the coins have designs such as the altar
of the century, nine dragons, and millennium commemoration as well
as the inscriptions of the People's Republic of China, and the
year in Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
There are three designs on the reverse sides of the coins,
those in the center are a human eye, the earth and the face value,
surrounded by 12 designs such as auspicious clouds, satellites,
the dove of peace, the sun, wheat stalks, houses, water, trees,
the moon, a computer mouse, and the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
The bank also issued 20 gold coins each weighing 10 kg, which
are believed to be the heaviest of their kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
China once issued gold coins weighing 5 kg each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
