<HEADLINE> Scholar Stresses Ecological Protection in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese scholar has
urged greater attention to ecological protection while developing
the vast western region, which is suffering from a deteriorating
environment.
</P>
<P>
The forest area of most of western China is sparse, with the
coverage rate for the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region only 0.79
percent, and 0.35 percent for Qinghai Province, 1.54 percent for
Ningxia, 4.33 percent for Gansu and 5.84 percent for the Tibet
Autonomous Region, said Jiang Zehui, president of the Chinese
Academy of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Declining vegetation, soil erosion, and ever-worsening
desertification have seriously hindered economic construction and
social development in the western region, Jiang said in an article
in the Science Times.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China Central Committee and the State
Council are very concerned about the ecological environment of the
west, and have given priority to the region's ecological
protection and improvement.
</P>
<P>
To halt the sharp decline of forests areas in the region, the
State Forestry Administration plans to launch two strategic
afforestation projects in the west, one to protect natural forests
at the upper reaches of the Yangtze and Yellow rivers, the two
longest rivers in China, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Logging is forbidden in these areas, and some farmland
gradually will be reconverted to forest and grassland.
</P>
<P>
The other project, focusing on the desert areas in northwest,
north and northeast China, aims to control the expansion of
desertification and rehabilitate the ecological system there.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zehui emphasized that awareness of this situation among
residents in the west should also be strengthened to improve their
knowledge of ecological protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
