<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Calls for Nature Reserve for Rare Yangtze River Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist recently
called for the creation of a nature reserve along the Chishui
River, a tributary on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, for
rare and endangered fish.
</P>
<P>
During an academic meeting on sustainable development in
western China, Cao Wenxuan, a member of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS), said the Chishui River is a perfect habitat for
the rare fish of the Yangtze River, and it is not suitable to
build a hydraulic power plant on the river.
</P>
<P>
In order to protect the 103 varieties of rare fish living in
the Yangtze River, the Wuhan Institute of Hydrobiology under the
CAS launched a research project to choose the best place to build
this reserve.
</P>
<P>
The nature reserve will become a home where the fish can
propagate after the completion of the Three Gorges Dam project,
said Cao.
</P>
<P>
A group of zoologists investigated more than 40 tributaries on
the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, and based on the
investigation they concluded that the Chishui River is the ideal
spot for the nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
There are no water projects and no serious pollution along the
Chishui River, which is 436.5 kilometers long and has a basin area
of 21,010 square kilometers, Cao said.
</P>
<P>
However, local governments are planning to build hydraulic
power plants on the river. Cao urged prudent thought before
construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
