<HEADLINE> Share Prices Inch Up on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed marginally
firmer on Singapore Stock Market Tuesday, posting a broad
downtrend in the morning under pressure of the overnight sharp
fall on the Nasdaq in the United States and staging a late
recovery to shrug off earlier trading losses.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index inched up 4.45 points to end
at 2,131.38 points, moving in the shape of a saddle and bouncing
back from the intraday low of 2,098.16 points in thin trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume dropped to 165.14 million shares worth 393.37
million Singapore dollars (228.65 million U.S. dollars). There
were 197 losers against 100 gainers with 232 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
LafeTech remained at the top of the actives chart with 12.95
million counters changing hands. It was followed by SingTel which
had 9.04 million shares done. JurTech came the third registering a
turnover of 8.77 million units.
</P>
<P>
Gr Eastern and SIA led gainers of the day gaining 50 cents each
to close at 23.50 and 15.50 Singapore dollars, respectively.
Datacrft picked up 35 cents to finish at 8.20 U.S. dollars. SIA
200 ended 30 cents higher at 15.50 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 was the biggest loser of the day plunging by 380
cents to close at 47.50 Singapore dollars. DBS sank 70 cents to
finish at 22.00 Singapore dollars. PacCent slid by 50 cents to end
at 14.90 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the market opened broadly lower weighed down
by the sharp overnight plunge on the U.S. Nasdaq but hike in the
afternoon offset earlier losses and rebounded.
</P>
<P>
They said that sentiment for tech stocks was shaky for most of
the day after the Nasdaq's almost-six-percent slump overnight as
investors were continually haunted by doubts over the Nasdaq's
performance and concern over possible U.S. interest hike.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that SIA bucked the overall downtrend
encouraged by New Zealand government's approval for it to buy up
to 8.3 percent of the share capital of the New Zealand Airline.
</P>
