<HEADLINE> Former Nigerian Opposition Leader Calls for Sovereign National Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former opposition leader
Anthony Enahoro Monday said Nigeria was not yet a democratic
country, and called upon a Sovereign National Conference to
address pertinent questions about the country.
</P>
<P>
Enahoro, who arrived in Lagos from a four-year exile in the
United States was welcomed like a hero at the airport of the West
African country' s largest city, according to This Day, a leading
Nigerian newspaper on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We deceive ourselves if we think that we've got to where we
are going," he said, adding that Nigerians need to determine
their relationships with one another, the paper quoted him as
saying during his visit to the residence of Lagos State Governor
Bola Tinubu.
</P>
<P>
He told in Yoruba language to thousands of his supporters, who
are mostly Yorubas, criticizing the current "zoning policy" of
the ruling People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Enahoro was one of the founding fathers of new Nigeria, who
fought tirelessly to press Britain to accept Nigeria's
independence in October, 1960.
</P>
<P>
His chequered political history included a stint as
commissioner (minister) for information, culture, youth, sports,
co-operatives and labor during the period from 1967 to 1974.
</P>
<P>
Enahoro, along with other eminent Nigerians, formed the
Nigeria's National Democratic Coalition to protest the military
annulment of the 1993 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Enahoro was briefly detained in 1994 by the regime of late
military leader Sani Abacha, before he fled the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately clear if the former opposition leader,
who is now vigorously agitating for a nationalism platform, still
has energy for Nigeria's rigorous politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
