<HEADLINE> First Bulgarian Cargo Ship Sail Through Danube </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A Bulgarian cargo ship with two
barges sailed through the Novi Sad reach on the Danube Monday,
bringing hopes of the re-opening of the river which was blocked
during NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
Three bridges on the river in Yugoslavia were destroyed by NATO,
stranding until today six Bulgarian cargo ships and 25 barges in
the upper reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Minister of Transport and Communications Antoni
Slavinski said Monday that the passage of the Bulgarian vessel,
Sredna Gora, was successful only after Yugoslavia took provisional
measures. The cleanup of the river, which is a key trade route
between Eastern and Western Europe, remains a political issue, the
Standard newspaper quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has insisted that any
cleanup operation must be accompanied by rebuilding of the
destroyed bridges while the West strongly opposes the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held in Budapest on Monday, the Danube Commission,
which oversees the river's traffic, put the cleanup cost at 24.1
million euros (24.4 million U.S. dollars), 85 percent of which
will be paid by the European Union and the rest shared by
countries along the river. 
</P>
</TEXT>
