<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Crocodile "Bites" Hong Kong Crocodile in Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- La Chemise Lacoste, the France-
based producer of men's shirts, brought a Hong Kong-based garment
company to court here today for violation of a registered trade
mark: a crocodile.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Supreme People's Court held a public hearing of the
case with more than 100 Chinese and foreign spectators.
</P>
<P>
La Chemise Lacoste charged that crocodile design has been
registered as a trade mark in 129 countries around the world since
it was created in 1933.
</P>
<P>
But the French crocodile discovered a twin crocodile in 1995.
Without permission from La Chemise Lacoste, Hong Kong-based
Crocodile Garments Limited and its agent in Beijing also used the
crocodile trade mark on similar products.
</P>
<P>
The French crocodile therefore appealed to stop this violation,
and claimed compensation of 3.5 million yuan (about 421,600 U.S.
dollars). It also required an open apology from the Hong Kong
crocodile.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong crocodile proclaimed that as a well-known company
in Asia, it has used the design of the crocodile for decades. In
China's mainland alone, the Hong Kong crocodile has more than 260
outlets, they claimed.
</P>
<P>
Since the French crocodile and the Hong Kong crocodile appeal
to different groups of customers, the public is not confused by
the crocodile trade mark, said the Hong Kong company.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong crocodile emphasized that its clothing
accessories are only available in special outlets, and this
prevents customer confusion.
</P>
<P>
It has been noticed that in the eyes of ordinary customers, the
biggest difference is that the French crocodile faces right, and
the Hong Kong crocodile faces left. The label also differs, since
La Chemise Lacoste uses "Lacoste" while the Crocodile Garment Ltd.
uses "Crocodile."
</P>
<P>
After a show of evidence and debate, the judge announced that
the verdict would be announced later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Boosts Offshore Oil and Gas Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China expects an annual average
increase of 20 percent in offshore oil and gas production from
2000 to 2005, as it launches a massive development of its new oil
and gas fields.
</P>
<P>
The country expects to enhance its offshore oil and gas outputs
equivalent to 40 million tons by 2005, according to Wei Liucheng,
president of the China National Offshore Oil Corp (CNOOC).
</P>
<P>
China has discovered a group of large-sized oil and gas bearing
structures in the Bohai Sea, South China Sea and East China Sea
which are all rich in oil and gas reserves, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The Penglai 19-3 structure in the bay areas of Bohai Sea is
particularly large with proven crude reserves hitting 300 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield is expected to be developed in the latter half of
this year and be put into operation by 2004 with an annual
production capacity of 15 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The Xihu Depression in the basin of the East China Sea is
particularly rich in gas resources with proven and probable gas
reserves topping 150 billion cubic meters. Experts expect the
total gas resources in the Xihu Depression to hit one to two
trillion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
In addition to gas, the Xihu Depression is also rich in oil
resources with total resources reaching 1.2 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
Wei noted that CNOOC has set 2000 as its "Gas Development Year",
and is giving priority to developing offshore gas in the East
China Sea. So far, drilling operation has started in the Shaoxing
6-1 structure in the Xihu Depression.
</P>
<P>
Large-sized offshore oil and gas projects which have been
launched or to be launched include the second-phase project of
Suizhong 36-1, Qinhuangdao 32-6, Wenchang 13-1/2, Panyu 5-1,
Caofeidian 11-1, Bozhong 29-4 and Bozhong 25-1 in the Bohai Sea
and South China Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
