<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Commentary Criticizes Formalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China's official news agency
Xinhua released a special commentary today exposing the harm of
formalism and calling for resolute efforts to get rid of the
bureaucratic style.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, some localities have favored formalism, that
is, cooking official accounts and exaggerating their working
performances, and this has had a very bad influence on society,
the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
Despite the various forms it may take, formalism actually stems
from a deviation from Party policies, and from the individualism
that exists among some leading officials.
</P>
<P>
These officials often hope that through boasting and
exaggerating their performances they will impress their superiors
and thereby gain promotions to higher positions.
</P>
<P>
"Formalism has gravely undermined the relationship between the
Party and the people, and between the government and the masses,
sullying the image of the Party and the government," the
commentary notes.
</P>
<P>
To combat formalism, it is first of all imperative to
straighten out the line of thinking of officials, according to the
commentary.
</P>
<P>
Seeking truth from facts has been the line of thinking of the
Party, and it is by sticking to this line that the Party has
overcome many difficulties in leading the nation forward.
Formalism is just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
In the process, leading officials should take a lead, and
democracy should be given full play, the commentary stresses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
