<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Book Labels on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Ancient book labels, including
two in German books published in 1575, are now being displayed at
the National Library of China in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Originating in Germany in the 15th Century, book labels are
considered a kind of miniature art. They are put inside book
covers using block-print technique to print the owners' names,
titles, or maxims.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is the first in China showing classic Western
book labels in rare editions of books in Western languages
collected by the library.
</P>
<P>
The two German labels were the earliest collections by Chinese,
only 10 years later than the world's earliest, collected by
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Two labels in Chinese on Western books published in 1735 and
1902 are also part of the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
Book labels spread to China in the early 20th Century, and the
first were used in two albums published in 1909.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition also shows that the National Library of China
was the first library in the country to use these labels. In the
1930s, the library started releasing two kinds: block-prints in
Western books the library bought, and those in Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition started this past weekend and will run until
early June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Tourists to Macao Up 41.8 Pct in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of visitors to the
Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) in tour groups was more
than 129,900 in February this year, an increase of 41.8 percent
over that of February 1999, latest official figures show.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 68 percent of the visitors came from the inland areas of
the China and about 18.4 percent came from Taiwan, according to
figures released by the Statistics and Census Services of the
Macao SAR government.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of the year, the number of visitors to
Macao in tour groups exceeded 236,000 increasing by 40.4 percent
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, 13,626 Macao residents, out of a population
of some 430,000, traveled to other places in tour groups in
February, a decrease of 15.6 percent from the same month of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The most favored destination of tour for Macao residents was
China's inland areas which accommodated 76.7 percent of the total
tourists from Macao in February.
</P>
<P>
During the first two months of this year as a whole, the number
of Macao residents traveling to other places in tour groups
dropped 13.8 percent from the same period of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
