<HEADLINE> Lebanon Uncovers Bin Laden Partisans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese security authorities have
arrested a 10-member terrorist group linked to the Saudi-expelled
billionaire-terrorist Osama Bin Laden, which was planning a new
plot to "destabilize the country," Daily Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
A judicial source disclosed on Monday that the suspected
terrorists were led by an Egyptian named Jamal Tantawi, who fought
alongside with Bin Laden during the Afghan war in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A military prosecutor has formally charged them with
participation in underground religious extremist cells aimed at
destabilizing the country through terrorist acts, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The source refused to disclose when or where the group members
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Ambassador Ade Khodari has talked with Public
Prosecutor Adnan Addoum on extraditing Tantawi while Addoum ruled
out any extradition before the group has been tried and said the
defendants have to serve their sentences in Lebanon if convicted.
</P>
<P>
Among the arrested were Egyptians, Palestinians, Lebanese and a
Syrian.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden has topped the United States' list of most-wanted
terrorists after he was charged with masterminding two explosions
of American embassies in Tanzania and Kenya in 1998 in which 224
people were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
