<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Police Give Reward on Clue for Arrest of Cult Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan police have announced a
reward of 12 million shillings (8,000 U.S. dollars) to those who
will provide information for the arrest of the six main leaders of
the cult Movement for the Restoration of the Ten Commandments of
God, the Monitor newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Police Spokesman Asuman Mugenyi as saying
that they had put up a reward of two million shillings (1,333 U.S.
dollars) to anybody who gives a clue leading to the arrest of
each of the six cult leaders including Joseph Kibwetere, founder
of the cult organization.
</P>
<P>
Over 530 cult members and their children were burnt to death in
a nailed shut church building in Kanungu in southwestern Uganda on
March 17. About 500 bodies of cult members have since been
exhumed in mass graves around the area.
</P>
<P>
Mugenyi said the police needed body bags, protective wear,
disinfectants and land for reburying the exhumed bodies of those
murdered by the cult leaders.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the Kanungu incident, Ugandan police required the
International Criminal Police Organization to help arrest the cult
leaders who are said to be still on the run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
