<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's 1999 Imports from Africa up: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- China took measures to encourage
imports from Africa in 1999 to offset its trade surplus, said a
senior Chinese trade official here today.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the opening ceremony of a seminar for Chinese
and African economic officials, He Xiaowei, Chinese Assistant
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said that
China's imports from Africa in 1999 reached 2.37 billion U.S.
dollars, up 60.9 percent from that in 1998 thanks to efforts made
by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 trade between China and Africa totaled 8.48 billion U.
S. dollars, 17.2 percent more than in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
China invested a total of 130 million U.S. dollars in Africa
last year, and set up 64 enterprises in the continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises have also gained access to the African
construction market with their good quality and low prices,
according to He. 
</P>
</TEXT>
