<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Bezeq company's monopoly on Israel's telephone and
Internet infrastructure will be broken in a few months, as soon as
the government and the Knesset (parliament) approve an amendment in
the Bezeq Law to allow cable-TV companies to compete in these
markets.
</P>
<P>
Communications Minister Binyamin Ben-Eliezer will bring his
proposal for the amendment to the government by Independence Day in
May.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Residents of the Israeli-occupied "security zone" in south
Lebanon have in recent weeks formed "civil guard" units to carry
out for operation prior to Israeli troops pullout this July.
</P>
<P>
These units are designed to act alongside the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) and might replace the SLA after the Israeli
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
At first, according to Israeli security officials, civil guard
members will be armed with firearms owned privately by local
residents. However, the militia could in the future be furnished by
SLA weapons.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will tell United States
President Bill Clinton at their White House summit Tuesday that he
is intending to make progress in talks with the Palestinians but "
you need two to tango."
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations said Barak
will present a framework agreement plan and Israel's own redlines
to Clinton during the meeting, agreeing to a Palestinian
independent state on 60 percent of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
land.
</P>
<P>
Israel is trying to reach a framework agreement with
Palestinians in the coming months. The target date for concluding
the document was currently set for May 13 after its original date
of February 13 passed.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Barak came away after his talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Cairo Monday as pessimistic
about success on the Syrian peace track as he had felt before the
meeting, a source aboard Barak's plane to Washington said Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
The official confirmed recent reports that Syrian had hardened
its stance and said the meeting Tuesday in Washington with Clinton
would therefore focus primarily on the Palestinian peace track.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Syria's demand to have access to Lake Kinneret (Sea of
Galilee) as part of any peace deal, the official reiterated the
government's position, saying that Israel has one fresh-water lake
and it is a top national priority to maintain full authority over
that lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
