<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Garment, Textile Exports Up 10.5 Pct in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine garments and textile
exports rose 10.5 percent to 713.96 million U.S. dollars in March
from 645.99 million dollars in the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Garments and Textile Export Board showed that
exports to quota countries reached 628.16 million dollars from 562.
38 million dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Among countries covered by quotas, the highest rate of increase
was recorded in the European Union with a 19.6 percent improvement
to 79.8 million dollars. Exports to Canada surged 13.89 percent,
followed by 10.25 percent growth in exports to the Untied States.
</P>
<P>
The United States continues to be the country's most important
market, accounting for 74.98 percent of the country's total
exports.
</P>
<P>
Among the positive economic indicators under the Estrada
presidency is the robust performance of the export sector, which
generated 35 billion dollars of earnings last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's export to non-quota countries also registered an
increase of 2.62 percent or 2.19 million dollars
</P>
<P>
The top five garment and textile importers are Japan at 29.18
million dollars; Hong Kong at 9.35 million dollars; Untied Arab
Emirates at 6.74 million dollars; Taiwan at 4.98 million dollars;
and Panama at 3.53 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Apparel exports continue to dominate the export scene,
accounting for 80.40 percent of total exports, with textile-based
non-apparel items and textile products following at 15.72 percent
and 3.88 percent,respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
