<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's MSC Attracts Huge Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC) has so far received investments of 3.416 billion
ringgit (898.947 million U.S. dollars), Energy, Communications and
Multimedia Ministry Parliamentary Secretary Chia Kwang Chye said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 302 companies have achieved MSC status that could
enjoy one of two types of incentives available -- pioneer status
or exemption from investment tax, he said in Parliament here.
</P>
<P>
Of the total investments, European companies are the top
foreign investors with 39 European companies investing 200.77
million ringgit (52.834 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second highest investment came from 12 Singapore companies
with 133.95 million ringgit (35.25 million dollars), followed by
25 companies from the United States with 129.32 million ringgit(34.
031 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Many other companies have invested in the projects, including
10 from Japan, five from Australia, four from Canada, 11 from
other Asian countries and 18 from other parts of the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
MSC is a 50 by 15 kilometer belt zone stretching southward from
Kuala Lumpur, designed specially for hi-tech ventures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parties to CITES Urged to Develop Laws on Wildlife Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal Police
 Organization (Interpol) has warned that the legal framework and
enforcement structures in fighting wildlife crime in some
countries are non-existent.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, not all parties to the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) have introduced
their own national laws to penalize the illegal trade in
endangered species of wild fauna and flora," secretary-general of
the Interpol Raymond Kendall said in his article published by the
latest issue of the United Nations Environment Program's magazine
Our Planet.
</P>
<P>
In the article titled Interpol Alert, Kendall said that it was
urgent that all parties should develop proper enforcement
structures and appropriate laws that internationally harmonized.
</P>
<P>
It is a relatively new crime area for law enforcement agencies
worldwide, Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the numbers of some endangered species have
recently diminished significantly and illegal hunting is one
factor behind this dramatic decline in numbers.
</P>
<P>
"Interpol is actively engaged in the fight against wildlife
crime," Kendall added.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the Interpol working group on wildlife
crime was held in the Netherlands in 1994 and objectives of
cooperation among different countries were worked out, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on member countries of CITES to take effective law
enforcement measures against the crime in order to safeguard the
environment and protect the planet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0235 </DOCNO>
