<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Finds Enormous Demand for IT Workers in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. employers can fill less
than half of the information technology jobs available next year,
indicating that the country is ill-equipped to staff the source of
its economic growth, according to an industry group study released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Information Technology Association of America (ITAA)
determined in its study that IT work force in the United States
numbers over 10 million and needs 1.6 million more workers in 2000.
Hiring managers foresee a shortfall of almost 850,000
appropriately skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
"The nation's economic future is tied to the availability of
appropriately skilled workers," ITAA President Harris Miller said.
</P>
<P>
Technical support representatives, database developers, and Web
administrators and programmers are the top three most in-demand IT
careers, the study shows.
</P>
<P>
Employers will seek to fill over 600,000 jobs for tech support
personnel alone over the next 12 months. Workers with Web-related
skills are the target of 13 percent of all IT hiring, according to
the study.
</P>
<P>
The study also finds that although traditional training
providers such as colleges and private schools are considered
effective, employers expressed a strong preference for creating
their own formal, on-the-job training programs.
</P>
<P>
Training after the employee is hired is rated by the managers
as significantly more effective than pre-hire methods of training.
Four-year colleges and private technical institutes were rated
highest among pre-hire skill acquisition methods when comparing
all positions.
</P>
<P>
Study results are based on a random sample of 700 IT managers,
both inside and outside the IT industry. ITAA consists of 400
direct and 26,000 affiliate corporate members throughout the U.S.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Pro-Nazi Writer Gets One-Year Jail Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A Swiss writer has been given a
one-year jail term by a Lausanne court for denying the Holocaust
and Nazi war crimes, Radio International reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gaston-Armand Amaudruz, nearly 80 years old, was found guilty
of racial discrimination following a three-day trial held last
week in Lausanne correctional court.
</P>
<P>
The charges were based on an article in Amaudruz's magazine, Le
Courrier du Continent, and 24 revisionist books.
</P>
<P>
In the magazine article, he denied for lack of proof the
existence of Nazi gas chambers where Jews were systematically
executed.
</P>
<P>
"For my part, I maintain my position: I don't believe in the
gas chambers. Let the exterminationists provide the proof and I
will believe it. But as I've been waiting for this proof for
decades, I don't believe I will see it soon."
</P>
<P>
The revisionist writer also insisted it was "impossible" for
six million Jews to have been murdered by the Nazis during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
Amaudruz was charged under Switzerland's 1995 anti-racism law,
which makes it a criminal offense to "deny, grossly minimize or
seek to justify genocide or other crimes against humanity."
</P>
<P>
It is thought that Amaudruz first came into contact with Nazis
engaged in the German legation in Berne during World War Two when
Switzerland was neutral. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
