<HEADLINE> No Casualties In Wholesale Market Fire in Kunming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- No casualties have been reported
following Monday's large fire which destroyed a wholesale market
in Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province, Xinhua
has learned.
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out at the Nanyao Cosmopolitan Wholesale Market
at 5:00 p.m. Beijing time Monday, and was extinguished by 00:30 a.
m. this morning.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zigang, deputy chief of the Yunnan Provincial Fire
Department, said the fire destroyed more than 400 business stands
and over 250 adjacent residential houses, involving an area of 10,
000 square meters. It was the most serious fire in the city in
recent years, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 500 firefighters participated in controlling the
blaze, and by early Tuesday morning ten people had been rescued
from the building. No bodies were found, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Sources at a local hospital said three people were injured in
the fire, and two firefighters suffering from noxious fumes were
said to be in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
The cause of fire and total economic losses are still under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
The Nanyao market had more than 1,500 business stands covering
an area of over 50,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The local fire department said that the fire-control equipment
at the market has not gone through the required examinations.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the ongoing Kunming International
Tourism Festival, which opened here Monday, was not affected by
the fire, and all activities at the festival are going on smoothly
as scheduled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
