<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-registered Domain Names Cause Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Domain names are being stolen by
others, although the practice is not illegally.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the top 100 listed firms in China don't
have domain names in Pinyin, or Romanization of their Chinese
names on the Net. Neither do 75 percent of the most popular 20
brands, according to 3721.com, a website offering domain name
registration service.
</P>
<P>
Such practices occurred in the United States and other
countries as well, whereby big companies have to pay large ransom
to buy back their "names".
</P>
<P>
A couple of years ago, registration of domain names of famous
Chinese firms in English was found rampant overseas, either by
institutions or individuals.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese firms realized the importance of their domain
names, but only registered them under the China domain, ending
with ".cn".
</P>
<P>
Domain names previously registered by others have found to be
rampant in the past six months, especially from February to March
this year. Some of the applicants are Chinese, said Hu Haidi, vice
president of 3721.com.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Internet users are most familiar with the Pinyin of
those big companies, and may be misled to other websites under the
name of the companies.
</P>
<P>
Hu has called for enterprises to protect themselves by applying
for domain names as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
