<HEADLINE> Kenya to Upgrade Satellite Earth Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to spend
401 million shillings (around 5.5 million U.S. dollars) to upgrade
its Longonot International satellite earth station, about 50
kilometers northwest of the capital Nairobi, the East African
Standard newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The upgrading project is seen as critical for Telkom Kenya, the
state- owned telecommunications corporation, in its efforts to
boost traffic capacity in liberalizing telecommunications sector
and also a major step to improve the country's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Vertex RSI, an American company, and its local partner are
currently installing a new digital transmission to replace the
old analog technology at the station.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide training opportunities to
Telkom's technical staff through follow-on operations and
maintenance support, said John Geiling, vice-president of Vertex
RSI.
</P>
<P>
Upon the completion of the project by the end of this year,
there will be a significant increase of access to international
lines in order to meet the twin demands of the mobile phone and
the internet service, Geiling said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
