<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Enterprises Call for Legal Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China classifies cases of corruption within the category of
state-owned enterprises as criminal cases, whereas corruption
cases within the category of private enterprises are classified as
civil cases, leading to more lenient penalties for the latter.
</P>
<P>
Sun Fuling, vice-chairman of the Ninth National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Committee,
acknowledged that regardless of who owns assets, who uses them and
who benefits from them, they actually remain in China and benefit
the country.
</P>
<P>
Lack of regulations and laws concerning market operation have
been a major cause of corruption within the government departments.
</P>
<P>
China has a new constitution that gives equal emphasis to state-
owned, collectively-owned enterprises and private enterprises. And
what is crucial at present is to further strengthen the people's
legal consciousness, acquaint themselves with the related laws and
regulations, and enable them to know still more clearly their
rights and obligations concerning the laws, Sun said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Enterprises Call for Legal Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China's old legal system should
be re-examined and amended to make way for a more just legal
system and to guarantee the future development of private
enterprises, according to "China Economic News".
</P>
<P>
A report to the 15th National Congress of Communist Party of
China (CPC) convened in 1997 and the new constitution passed at
the Second Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC)
reiterates that private enterprises are an important, integral
part of China's economy. However, there are numerous legal
problems which have yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
After China enters the World Trade Organization (WTO),
investors from overseas will be allowed to enter many Chinese
economic sectors such as telecommunications, railways, banking and
finance, but domestic private enterprises will be not be granted
the same privilege.
</P>
<P>
This will discourage public investment, and hinder China's
positive financial policy, economists said, adding that the narrow
investment scope is a major reason for the country's current low
domestic investment level.
</P>
<P>
Illegal levies on private enterprises are existent far and wide
in China, but many are not aware of their legal rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
