<HEADLINE> CPPCC Chairman Meets Singaporean PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), today told visiting Singaporean Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong that China is willing to learn from Singapore in
modernizing the country.
</P>
<P>
Li said that he was delighted to meet with Goh again in the
blossoming spring in the Chinese capital. He expressed his
admiration for the courage and wisdom of the Singaporean
government and people in handling the difficult situation amidst
the Asian financial crisis and the belief that Goh's current visit
will play an important part in promoting and developing China-
Singapore friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China's reform is "at a critical phase in tackling
tough issues." He said that reform and opening-up drive has
produced remarkable achievements over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, we also face a number of difficulties that must be
resolved such as oversupply of low-level production caused by an
irrational economic structure, reemployment and social security
issues brought about by establishment of modern enterprise system
among state-owned enterprises and laying off workers to increase
efficiency, and rampant corruption," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have been aware that all these problems appear in the
process of development. We firmly believe that we can resolve
these problems through our own efforts. However, we consider that
it is very important to learn from and draw on the successful
experience of foreign countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China is ready to learn every useful experience from Singapore
by all means and channels," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Goh told Li he had very good talks with Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji yesterday, during which the two sides exchanged views on
bilateral ties and issues of common concern. "The Singaporean
government highly values Singapore-China relations and hopes that
frequent contacts will continue to push forward bilateral
relations".  
</P>
</TEXT>
