<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia's Economy Improves As  Export Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- After the protracted economic and
financial crisis, value of Indonesia's export and import increased
significantly over the past months, showing a good progress of the
on-going economic recovery process.
</P>
<P>
Based on data issued by the Central Bureau of Statistic (BPS),
total export value during January 2000 reached 4.382 billion U.S.
dollars and increased again in February to 4.608 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, import also increased to 4.20 billion
dollars or 17.37 percent higher than the same period last year
when the figure was 3.58 billion dollars, the data showed.
</P>
<P>
Didik J. Rachbini, an economist of the Indonesian University,
said in an interview with Xinhua on Tuesday that the increase of
the total export value is a sign showing the country's economic
situation is improving.
</P>
<P>
"But actually, there are four components which should be used
to asses the economic situation comprehensively, namely,
consumption of the middle class society, export growth, investment
and budget," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the middle of last year, consumption of the middle class
society in Indonesia started improving, while export and import
also tended to increase, Rachbini said.
</P>
<P>
"But Indonesia has a problem in wooing investors due to lack of
security guarantee. And now, we have a lot of foreign debt that
has to be paid. These are problems for the country. And if such
problems can't be tackled well, (it) will hamper the recovery
process. But if settled well, the economic recovery process will
be faster," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief of Export Department at the BPS Dantes
Simbolon, in a separate interview with Xinhua, predicted that the
country's export value in March will be higher than the January
and February figures.
</P>
<P>
Simbolon said that the total export value in January and
February 2000 were 44.70 percent higher than the January-February
1999 figure when the country's total export value was 3.017,8
billion and 3.195 billion dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Central Bureau of Statistic Sugito Suwito
earlier also said that the increase of the export value was a sign
that the country's economy has been recovering.
</P>
<P>
Sugito explained that the increase of the total export value
for January-February this year was contributed by the increasing
of oil and gas export which reached 2.24 billion dollars or 82.90
percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
And the total export value of non-oil and gas reached 6.75
billion dollars or 35.34 percent higher than the same period last
year when the figure was 4.99 billion dollars, Suwito added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
