<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Tung Expects Disneyland to Boost Local Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 10 (Xinhua)-- Visiting Chief Executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), Tung Chee Hwa,
Monday expressed confidence that the proposed Hong Kong Disneyland
will strengthen the local economy and bring the region's tourism
to world-class standard.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on building the amusement park was reached last
year after nine-month negotiations between the HKSAR government
and Walt Disney Corporation. Tung visited the Disneyland and
Disney University in Southern California Monday morning before his
meeting with Walt Disney executives in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press in the company's headquarters, Tung said
Disney's innovative technology would help upgrade Hong Kong's
entertainment industry. The project will also benefit other
sectors and communities in Hong Kong by offering development and
employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing his visit to Canada and the United States, Tung said
his meetings with U.S. and Canadian leaders as well as officials
in commercial, industrial and political arenas have been very
useful.
</P>
<P>
"I clearly have the feeling that both the United States and
Canada recognize the fact that 'one country, two systems' has been
successful in Hong Kong. Both countries want to have even closer
economical and trade relations with Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with U.S. President Bill Clinton and
members of Congress, Tung said he stressed the importance of
granting China permanent normal trade relations status.
</P>
<P>
"This is not just good for Hong Kong's economy which is in the
process of recovery, not only good for China, but also very good
for the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to environmental protection, Tung said he visited
the environmental protection department in Toronto, Canada, and
will visit similar agencies in Los Angeles and Southern California
"to learn how they are going with environmental protection,
particularly in the area of air quality which is the issue Hong
Kong is most concerned with."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about Taiwan, Tung said: "As a Chinese
and the chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, I strongly wish our country would realize reunification as
early as possible on the basis of 'one China', and 'one country,
two systems'."
</P>
<P>
When Taiwan embraces the "one country, two systems" system,
Tung said, the mechanism will not necessarily be exactly the same
as Hong Kong's, because Taiwan and Hong Kong have different
backgrounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
