<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economy Predicted to Remain Robust in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The dynamics of the U.S.
economy and housing market are changing but still favorable,
according to a report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Higher interest rates, volatility in the stock market and
rising oil prices are starting to erode consumer confidence and
will dampen economic growth, said the report from the National
Association of Realtors (NAR), America's largest trade association.
</P>
<P>
"However, housing demand continues to be strong and mortgage
financing remains fairly affordable, so this year will still be in
the top three as far as markets go."
</P>
<P>
According to the NAR, part of the current housing market's
strength results from equity gains in both home ownership and the
stock market. With increasing volatility in the stock market, more
people would diversify their portfolios by investing in real
property.
</P>
<P>
The NAR expects U.S. home resales to drop 8.7 percent in 2000
to a total of 4.74 million units, while new-home sales are
expected to slide 5.3 percent to 858,000 units. Housing starts are
forecast to decline 3.6 percent in 2000 to 1.61 million units.
</P>
<P>
The association expects 30-year fixed-rate mortgage rates to
rise slightly to about 8.5 percent and hold at that level for most
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The NAR predicted that the U.S. economy will grow 4.4 percent
this year compared with a revised 4.2 percent growth rate in 1999.
Consumer price inflation should average 2.5 percent in 2000. The
unemployment rate is projected to average 4 percent compared with
4.2 percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
