<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philadelphia 76ers Beats Miami 96-80 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Allen Iverson's 33 points led
the Philadelphia 76ers to a 96-80 win over Miami on Monday night,
ending the Heat's seven-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
Eric Snow scored 12 points and 10 assists for Philadephia,
which stayed in fourth place in the Eastern Conference standings,
one game ahead of Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
Miami led early, but Iverson led his team back with 18 first-
half points. His layup with 9:08 left in the half made it 29-26
for Philadelphia, which never trailed again.
</P>
<P>
Tim Hardaway of Miami played just three minutes in the fourth
quarter and scored only four points. Jamal Mashburn led the Heat
with 16 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
In Toronto, Raptors outclassed Cleveland 112-103. Vince Carter'
s first career triple-double helped Toronto inch closer to its
first playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
Carter went 13-of-19 from the field and scored 31 points, had
11 rebounds and added a career-high 10 assists. Tracy McGrady
collected 27 points. Shawn Kemp had 22 points for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, Charlotte Hornets defeated Wizards 107-105.
Elden Campbell's 5 meter turnaround jumper as time expired capped
a wild finish for Charlotte, which has won nine of its last 11
games.
</P>
<P>
Eddie Jones scored 26 points and David Wesley had 21 for the
Hornets. Mitch Richmond had 21 points and reserve Richard Hamilton
19 for the Wizards, who had won 8 of 11.
</P>
<P>
The game was tied at 103 when Anthony Mason hit a 3 meter with
2.8 seconds left for a 105-103 lead. Richmond was fouled on the
ensuing inbounds play and hit both free throws, tying the game at
105 and setting up Campbell's game-winner.
</P>
<P>
In Boston, Celtics beat Hawks 99-94. Antoine Walker scored 26
of his 34 points in the second half, including a 3-pointer with 25
seconds left to cap a game-ending 11-0 Boston rally.
</P>
<P>
The win snapped Boston's 10 game-losing skid, its longest since
1997. Kenny Anderson was the only other Boston player in double
figures, with 24 points.
</P>
<P>
In New York, Knicks edged Pacers 83-81. Patrick Ewing made a
turnaround jumper with two seconds left, and apparently redirected
Larry Johnson's earlier 3-pointer into the basket, to lead New
York.
</P>
<P>
Ewing scored nine of the Knicks' final 12 points and appeared
to have a hand in the other three.
</P>
<P>
Reggie Miller tied the game at 81-81 on two foul shots with 15.
7 seconds left. The Knicks then got the ball to Ewing (20 points)
in the low post, and he sank a trademark fadeaway shot.
</P>
<P>
In Milwaukee, Bucks whitewashed Magic 104-87. Ray Allen scored
33 points, and Sam Cassell added 18 points and eight assists as
Milwaukee moved one game behind Orlando for the Eastern Conference
's final postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
The Bucks won for the sixth time in eight games.
</P>
<P>
In Minneapolis, Timberwolves routed Detroit Pistons 102-100.
Kevin Garnett of Minnesota shot in a 10-foot jumper at the horn.
Garnett scored 25 points, and Terrell Brandon added 16.
</P>
<P>
In Los Angeles, LA Lakers eliminated Seattle 106-103. Kobe
Bryant scored five of his 33 points in overtime as Los Angeles won
without Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal, the NBA's leading scorer and second-leading rebounder,
sat out his second game because of a sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
In Salt Lake City, Portland Trail Blazers overwhelmed Utah Jazz
90-86. Greg Anthony's 3-pointer with 21.8 seconds remaining gave
Portland a 3-1 win of the season series between the teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
