<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Puts Leaning Building Back to Right Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese architecture
experts have announced that they have successfully put a leaning
building back to the right position in downtown Harbin, capital
city of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
They said that the work was done in 1998, "close observations
in the past one and a half years showed that the building was in a
stable condition after being erected".
</P>
<P>
The Qilu Mansion, 28-floor and 96 meters in height, was found
leaning with its gradient nearly three times higher than permitted.
A group of experts from the Heilongjiang Provincial Academy of
City Planning and Design and the Beijing Jiaotong University were
asked to erect the leaning building.
</P>
<P>
The experts dug several upright wells on the opposite side of
the building's leaning direction, and then used high-pressure
water to wash out unwanted ground-soils to force the building into
the right position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
