<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Stresses Unity Among NAM Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has stressed the need for
unity among member countries of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM),
saying that at the start of the new century, developing countries
are faced with an international environment where the strong still
persist in their design to impose their values on others.
</P>
<P>
In his policy statement delivered at the plenary session of the
13th Ministerial Conference of the NAM held in Cartagena, Colombia
last Saturday, Myanmar Foreign Minister U Win Aung charged that
the noble institutions of the United Nations System are being used
by the strong to further their national interest and to exert
undue pressure on developing countries, official newspaper The New
Light of Myanmar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is distressed by a trend of increasing tendency to use
or rather misuse the issues of democracy, human rights and
environment by strong and powerful countries to put undue pressure
on developing countries in the interest furthering their hidden
political or economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
The developing countries find themselves in situation where
negatives are accentuated and the positives completely ignored by
international media, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Myanmar has been the target of political pressure
by some western countries and is accused of practicing forced
labor.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the regret that the International Labor
Organization (ILO) persists in carrying out concerted action to
take drastic measures against Myanmar at the forthcoming
International Labor Conference.
</P>
<P>
He hopes the NAM member countries will regard this ILO attempt
as a coercive action taken against a fellow developing country for
reason which he said entirely unrelated to the promotion of rights
of labor.
</P>
<P>
On Yugoslavia issue, he said Myanmar hopes to see the creation
of conditions which would enable Yugoslavia to rejoin soonest the
NAM of which that country has been a founding member.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized the need for peace and security for
economic development of all nations, saying that Myanmar, in line
with its independent and active foreign policy and upholding the
principles of peaceful coexistence, maintains friendly ties with
all nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the new century, the developing countries are
faced with the impossible task of managing their domestic
economies in an increasingly integrated global economy.
</P>
<P>
In wake of the East Asian crisis, which is a crisis of
globalization, he stressed the need for the reform of the
international financial system.
</P>
<P>
In the new century, unity among NAM member countries is more
urgent than ever, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is a founding member of the NAM. The country once
suspended its participation in the movement in 1979 but resumed
its activities beginning with the 10th NAM Summit in Indonesia in
September 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Business Summit Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 11 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN Business Summit 2000
with the theme "Asia 2000: Moving Forward" opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit will discuss on how ASEAN in the new
millennium can sustain recovery and enhance integration, how the
changes in world geo-political power are affecting ASEAN, what are
foreign investors' perspectives of ASEAN, how to enhance growth in
East Asia through closer collaboration, how ASEAN can meet the
challenges ahead,and on strategies and collective initiatives that
can be taken to regain ASEAN's economic competitiveness in the
wake of the new economy of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi
officiated the summit on behalf of his Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad who went to Havana to attend the G-77 summit.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah read out Mahathir's speech at the opening in which
Mahathir outlined three key issues -- globalization,
liberalization and mega-mergers -- ASEAN should focus upon to
achieve its goals of establishing ASEAN of a concert and a
community of Southeast Asian nations, outward looking, living in
peace, stability and prosperity, bonded together in partnership in
dynamic development and in a community of caring societies by the
year 2020.
</P>
<P>
On globalization, Mahathir said "The globalization can be good
if we have a say in its interpretation. It will be good if we can
have some control over the movements across our borders."
</P>
<P>
He said "We should say: no globalization without benefit, no
globalization without self determination, and no globalization
without corporate responsibility or conscience."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of liberalization, he said domestic liberalization
and cross-border liberalization, and national market
liberalization and international market liberalization should be
distinguished.
</P>
<P>
"Even as we say a qualified 'yes' to international
liberalization,we should say: no international liberalization
without benefit, no international liberalization without self-
determination, no international liberalization without regulation,
no international liberalization without representation, and no
international liberalization without corporate responsibility and
conscience."
</P>
<P>
On the global mega-mergers, Mahathir said "These global mega-
mergers may be great for others. But the question has to be asked:
is it good for us?"
</P>
<P>
The summit is jointly organized by the National Chamber of
Commerce and Industry of Malaysia (NCCIM) and the Asian Strategy
Leadership Institute under the auspices of the ASEAN Chamber of
Commerce and Industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
