<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Crack Down on Errant Job Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will take action
against errant employment agencies who send job seekers to foreign
countries on student visas, the Bureau of Foreign Employment said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the bureau said those errant employment
agencies had sent more than 300 Sri Lankans to Cyprus during the
past few months on student visas promising them employment there.
</P>
<P>
However, those job seekers now face punitive action and
deportation in Cyprus, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
According to the existing migrant laws in Cyprus, foreigners
with student visas are not allowed to seek employment.
</P>
<P>
At present nearly 7,700 Sri Lankan workers are legally employed
in Cyprus, out of whom 5,200 are employed as housemaids.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan job seekers are allowed to be employed legally in
Cyprus only if they have a valid employment certificate from the
Bureau of Foreign Employment, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
