<HEADLINE> Mindanao Mayors Call for Extension of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Mayors in the southern Philippines
have asked President Joseph Estrada to extend for one more year
the peace negotiations between the government and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF), Philippine News Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The request came after an earlier deadline set by the president
for the negotiating parties to wrap up their talks by June this
year.
</P>
<P>
The League of Municipal Mayors in Maguindanao province,
Mindanao said the extension, once heard, will enable the
government to convert acknowledged MILF camps into economic zones.
</P>
<P>
Taking cue from the conversion of Datu Paglas town, once a
known lair of Moro rebels, into an income-generating zone by the
coming in of Canadian-supported projects, South Upi mayor Michael
Sinsuat, the province's mayor's league president, said the
municipality is now the recipient of some 48 million U.S. dollars
worth of investments.
</P>
<P>
"There are hundreds of MILF rebels in Dat Paglas but they do
not carry their firearms because they work together in a big
banana plantation there," Sinsuat was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sinsuat stressed that the conversion of MILF claimed
territories into economic zones would be a better approach in
resolving conflict in the area.
</P>
<P>
"Surely, if we can just provide jobs to these rebels and give
them support like farming ventures, they will do away with their
guns and cooperate with the government," Sinsuat said.
</P>
<P>
He also assured the 100-percent support of the local chief
executives in the economic conversion of the MILF territories if
the extension appeal is okayed by President Estrada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
