<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Recover Lost Supply Route </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that ground troops backed by
air cover, artillery and the navy were able to wrest the three
kilometer stretch of highway between Muhamalai and Pallai on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The dawn-to-dusk operation met with heavy resistance from
rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) who were
using machine guns, rocket-propelled grenades, mortars and
artillery, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said 11 government troops personnel were killed and 190
wounded,most with minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
Rebel casualties are not known but estimated to be very high.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting for a separate homeland for minority
Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983, had gained
control of a part of the supply route in a surprise attack
recently designed to cut off the strategic Elephant Pass military
base from the Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The capturing of Elephant Pass, a vital road bridge linking the
mainland and the Jaffna peninsula, is LTTE's first step of their
efforts to retake the former stronghold of Jaffna which they lost
to government troops in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
