<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Makes Progress in Protecting Health of Women and Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region in
southwest China has made marked progress in protecting the health
of women and children over the past four years thanks to a
regional program, a local senior official said recently.
</P>
<P>
According to the program for the 1996-2000 period, Tibet's
public health projects for women and children covered 900,000
people in 23 counties and seven cities and prefectures. More than
700,000 women and children have benefited from the projects, said
Tubdain, director of Tibet's Health Department.
</P>
<P>
Tibet now has 46 public health institutions specially for women
and children, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are now eleven state-level "baby friendly hospitals" in
Tibet since building of such hospitals began in 1994. A total of 2,
322 medical personnel have been trained.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's Congress also
passed detailed regulations on the implementation of the law on
protection of health of mothers and children in Tibet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
