<HEADLINE> France, Sweden to Enhance Cooperation in EU Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French President
Jacques Chirac and Swedish Prime Minister Goeran Persson said on
Monday their countries would increase cooperation in European
Union issues ranging from EU expansion and reform to relations
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
They told a joint news conference after their talks that France
and Sweden would set up a joint panel to coordinate their efforts
within EU, stressing the need for more bilateral discussions on
how to carry out the EU reform and establish a mechanism to deal
with EU crises.
</P>
<P>
France and Sweden shared identical views on many EU issues,
they added.
</P>
<P>
France will take over the six-month rotating EU presidency on
July 1, followed by Sweden on January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders agreed that EU should develop a long-term
partnership with Russia, whose cooperation, they said, is vital to
the stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said he hoped to complete the EU reform within France's
term and further expand the 15-member organization. The French
president arrived here Monday for a two-day state visit at the
invitation of Swedish King Carl XVI Gustaf.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is expected to meet with Swedish parliament speaker
Birgitta Dahl later on Monday and the Swedish King during his stay,
the first French state visit in 16 years to the Nordic country.
</P>
<P>
He is accompanied by French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine,
European Affairs Minister Pierre Moscovici and a business group on
the trip.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
