<HEADLINE> Flood of the Century Hits Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government called
an emergency session Monday and declared a state of emergency for
eight states in eastern Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Orban Vitor said he approved 37.3 billion
forints (147 million U.S. dollars) in aid for flood protection.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian authorities warned that they were facing the "flood
of the century" from heavy rains and melting snow.
</P>
<P>
The country's second largest river, the Tisza, and its
tributaries have flooded more than 200,000 hectares. The
overflowing tributaries have ruined and destroyed many homes and
are threatening thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
Many residents have had to flee their homes and many schools in
the countryside have been closed.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 7,500 people are working to strengthen dykes
along the rivers. Hungary's armed forces are on alert and 1,000
soldiers have taken part in fighting the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
