<HEADLINE> Austria Holds Funeral for Former President Kirchschlaeger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The funeral for former Austrian
President Rudolf Kirchschlaeger, who died of a heart attack on
March 30 at age of 85, took place Monday morning in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Though the late president requested a simple funeral without
wreaths and foreign leaders in attendance, a rather elaborate
funeral ceremony was held for Kirchschlaeger at St. Stephen's
Cathedral in the Austrian capital.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 people, including Austrian President Thomas Klestil,
former President Kurt Waldheim, former Prime Minister Josef Klaus
and Victor Klima, leaders from all Austrian political parties, the
staff of the current government as well as Vienna's residents and
prominent figures, attended the funeral.
</P>
<P>
Kirchschlaeger was born in a poor family in Upper Austria in
1915. He worked as a barber and casual laborer to support his
family in his youth. In 1940, he became a judge after graduating
from Vienna University with a degree in jurisprudence.
</P>
<P>
In 1954, he entered into the Foreign Ministry, and became
Foreign Minister of Austria from 1970 to 1974.
</P>
<P>
As a modest and open-minded man, Kirchschlaeger was prestigious
and twice elected as Austrian President during 1974 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
During his political career, he visited China twice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
