<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Worried About Development Aid Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 77 expressed concern
Monday for what it described as the continual descent of official
assistance from rich countries to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
"We're exhorting developed countries to fulfill their
commitment to direct 0.7 of their gross domestic product (GDP) for
official development assistance," G-77 said in a draft joint
declaration.
</P>
<P>
In 1970, the United Nations General Assembly established the
goal for wealthy countries to earmark 0.7 percent of their GDP for
assistance to developing countries. Currently, only four --
Denmark, the Netherlands, Norway and Sweden -- have reached or
surpassed that mark. A majority of industrialized in the north
have failed to comply with their pledged development assistance.
</P>
<P>
The north-south dialogue is on top of the agenda of the South
Summit of G-77, slated for April 10-14, the largest gathering of
heads of state or government since the 1964 founding of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Official Development Assistance from the north to the south in
1992 reached 61 billion U.S. dollars. By 1997, the total had
fallen to 47.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of the United States, all members of OCED,
which unites the world's wealthiest nations, have reaffirmed their
pledge to bring development assistance for the south up to 0.7
percent of their respective GDPs.
</P>
<P>
G-77 also showed concern for Africa, saying the debt's growth,
reduction of official development assistance, and the fall of its
products' prices have worsened economic and social conditions in
the continent, according to the draft document.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77, with Nigeria holding its Chairmanship for the
year 2000, was established on June 15, 1964, by 77 developing
countries in Geneva. Although the membership of G-77 has increased
to 133 countries, the original name was retained because of its
historic significance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0363 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venture-Backed Companies Account for Majority of U.S. IPOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Venture-backed companies
continued to account for the bulk of U.S. initial public offerings
(IPOs) in the first quarter of 2000, an information service firm
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 139 offerings of the past quarter, 75 received venture
funding prior to the offering -- accounting for 53.8 percent of
the total, compared to 26 companies that went public a year ago,
said Venture Economics, the U.S. forecast information provider for
private equity professionals worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Even with the recent market turmoil, the firm said, the U.S.
market's appetite for new venture-backed issues continues strong
even as it shows some signs of slowing. Venture-backed companies
account for a full 65 percent, or 181, of the 277 companies
currently registered.
</P>
<P>
These impressive numbers follow on the hot performance of
venture-backed IPOs in 1999, when venture-backed IPOs returned 92.
6 percent for the year, according to Venture Economics.
</P>
<P>
In the benchmark year of 1996, the 280 venture-backed IPOs
accounted for just 32 percent of the initial public offering
market.
</P>
<P>
There are signs that the market is less sanguine about the
issues coming to market, the firm pointed out. While the average
offer size and the total post offer value of IPOs increased in the
first quarter, the average post offer value -- the market value of
the company at the offer price -- decreased from the 1999 fourth
quarter highs.
</P>
<P>
The average size for venture-backed IPOs in the first quarter
leaped to 102 million U.S. dollars, far outpacing the 67-million-
dollar average in the first quarter of 1999. The average post
offer value, however, decreased from 577 million dollars in the
last quarter of 1999 to 523 million dollars in the first quarter
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead the rest of the year, which experienced a turmoil
in the first few days in April, Venture Economics predicted that "
this year will be a watershed year to validate the information
technology investments made in the last three years."
</P>
<P>
Currently, the firm said, the IPO market continues to fuel the
expectations of both public and private investors. "The private
and public markets have become inextricably intertwined in recent
years," the firm said. "The public markets provide the liquidity
and lubrication that have reaped substantial rewards for the
venture capital company, their investors and their investee
companies. With record amounts of capital coming into the venture
industry and the growing skepticism in the press about the ability
of dot.com companies to sustain their business models, it is
encouraging to see that the public markets continue to be
receptive to new issues this year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0364 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong to Enlarge Swan Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Swan Lake in Rongcheng City,
the world's largest habitat for swans in east China's Shandong
Province, is to be enlarged from 6,600 to more than 10,000
hectares with a total investment of 25 million yuan (3.01 million
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The lake, which is an ideal habitat for swans in winter,
attracts thousands of swans from Siberia every year to spend
winter.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its picturesque coastal scenery, the lake has
also become a famous tourism attraction to large numbers of
overseas and domestic tourists.
</P>
<P>
Rongcheng, at the eastern end of the Shandong Peninsula, has
made great effort to improve the environment over the past decade.
It has also carried out a series of protection projects on the
lake, habitat of swan and other rare birds.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, more and more swans have flocked to the
lake in winter, said a local waterfowl expert, but the increasing
number of the swans also brought some problems. The lake cannot
provide sufficient food and cruising space for swans.
</P>
<P>
The enlargement project will solve these problems and offer the
swans a more comfortable living environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0365 </DOCNO>
