<HEADLINE> Spring Wheat Harmed by Adverse Weather in Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The planting of spring wheat is
slow due to bad climate, which will most likely lead a poor
harvest this year, according to the agricultural department of
Liaoning province, northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Snow, followed by cold weather, appeared in most areas of the
province in the past few weeks. As a result, spring wheat planting
fields are about 55,900 hectares, nearly 6,666 hectares less than
last year.
</P>
<P>
Investigation carried out by the department said that situation
is worse because of heavy snow and sharp temperature drop in the
areas such as Shenyang, capital of the province, and Anshan, a
major base of Chinese steel industry, in the northern and central
part of the province.
</P>
<P>
However, despite adverse weather conditions, farmers can grow
other crops and the total annual output of grain in Liaoning will
not be much affected, according to the department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
