<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday welcomed the
announcement of a summit between the Democratic People's Republic
of Korean and the Republic of Korea, saying it was "fundamental to
solving the problems of the Korean Peninsula."
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the announcement that the Republic of Korea and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea will hold an historic first
summit in June," White House spokesman Joe Lockhart read the
president statement. "Direct dialogue between the two Koreas is
something we have long advocated and is fundamental to solving the
problems of the Korean Peninsula. This announcement is testimony
to the wisdom and long-term vision of President Kim Dae-jung's
engagement policy. I congratulate both leaders on their decision
to meet."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also called South Korean
Foreign Minister Lee Joung-binn Monday to convey her strong
support for the announcement. (US-Clinton-Koreas)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cooperation among developing countries is top on the
agenda of the South Summit, the largest ever gathering of heads of
state or government in the 36-year-old Group of 77 (G-77), and the
Havana meeting is seen as the best chance to improve the
bargaining position of the developing South in trade with the
developed North.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 Monday held a meeting of senior officials in advance
of the first ever South Summit in Havana, the capital of Cuba, to
ponder over the current challenge facing the developing world,
including the impact of globalization and the South-South
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Developing countries face today the challenge of formulating
a common vision and constructing a platform for collective action
in order to achieve a comprehensive formulation and forceful
articulation of their concerns and objectives," said the G-77
chairman, Arthur Mbanefo, who is also the Nigerian permanent
representative to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The Havana Summit is a unique opportunity to renew the South'
s commitment to South-South cooperation and define an action plan
with clear targets and a time frame for its effective
implementation," he said. (Cuba-G-77)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGDHAD -- The third batch of 500 Iraqi prisoners of war (POWs)
released by Iran on Monday crossed the Iranian-Iraqi border and
set foot on Iraqi soil, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
It was just another tearful reunion. Many POWs wept with joy,
while their family members, overwhelmed by excitement and rejoice,
threw flowers and candies on them.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people have been waiting for their arrival in the
border region, said the INA, adding that many POWs have not been
able to see their loved ones for as long as 18 years.
</P>
<P>
Iran on Sunday morning unilaterally released 500 Iraqi POWs
left over from the 1980-88 bloody war between the two neighbors,
and it set free another batch of 500 on Sunday night. In all, 1,
500 Iraqi POWs have since been back home.
</P>
<P>
The fourth batch of 500 Iraqi POWs are expected to arrive in
Iraq on Tuesday, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been exchanging POWs in recent years in
a bid to improve strained relations.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that it had released 55,438 Iraqi POWs since 1981 on
103 occasions while Iraq freed 39,417 Iranian POWs in the same
period on 70 occasions. (Iraq-Iran-POWs)
</P>
</TEXT>
