<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China City Joins Auto-Cleansing Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Following 12 other cities,
Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan Province, has passed a
regulation on automobile emission control.
</P>
<P>
With the number of automobiles on road exceeding 200,000,
automobile emission has become the major source of urban pollution
in Changsha.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulation, the city will focus on
upgrading 50,000 vehicles to reduce the waste discharge this year.
By the end of next year, 90 percent of the automobiles in Changsha
will meet the State automobile emission discharge criteria.
</P>
<P>
Twelve cities including Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Chongqing
and Xi'an are accelerating the cleansing process of oil-driven
automobiles by spreading gas-fueled automobiles and those driven
by mixed fuels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
