<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA to Rule on Leeds' Fan Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body
UEFA will decide on Wednesday whether Turkish fans should be
banned from second leg of the UEFA Cup semi-final match in Leeds
on April 20.
</P>
<P>
UEFA confirmed it had received a request from Leeds and the
Football Association to bar the Turkish side's supporters.
</P>
<P>
The call came after two Leeds fans, Chris Loftus and Kevin
Speight were stabbed to death during riots on the eve of the first
leg in Istanbul, which Galatasaray won 2-0.
</P>
<P>
Leeds has been asked by UEFA whether it could guarantee
security if Turkish fans were admitted to the ground.
</P>
<P>
UEFA has also asked Galatasaray to withhold its 1,700 ticket
allocation until a decision is made.
</P>
<P>
Leeds chairman Peter Ridsdale said he believed UEFA will
support the club's request due to reprisal fears.
</P>
<P>
Turgay Vardar, spokesman for Galatasaray, said the club
canceled a plan on Monday to send a letter to UEFA requesting
details on security measures at Leeds.
</P>
<P>
Vardar said the club would wait for Leeds' response before
deciding whether to seek a neutral venue or ask that Leeds fans
also be banned.
</P>
<P>
UEFA officials were meeting in Geneva, Switzerland, on Monday
to decide what arrangements should be made for the flashpoint
match.
</P>
<P>
After the deaths of the two supporters, Leeds United officials
and fans were incensed that a minute's silence was not observed
before the game and that Galatasaray fans made slitting motions
towards the English fans.
</P>
<P>
Ten Turkish youths detained in the stabbing deaths of the two
Leeds men were released on Monday, while eight others were still
being held.
</P>
<P>
One man has reportedly confessed to one of the killings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0398 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wembley Stadium Redevelopment Faces Major Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The redevelopment of English
flagship stadium Wembley could be delayed for up to a year in a
row over the cost of building the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
Brent Council is due to announce the result of the planning
application for the new national football stadium on 25 April.
</P>
<P>
But a 30 million pounds short fall in the budget may mean that
necessary improvements to the rail and road links to the stadium
cannot be carried out.
</P>
<P>
If this is the case, the application is likely to be turned
down,causing a major delay in the redevelopment of the site that
is to be the jewel in the crown of England's 2006 World Cup bid.
</P>
<P>
The consortium behind the new Wembley is likely to appeal to
the Department of Environment if planning permission is rejected,
which could lead to a delay of anything up to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Wembley spokesman Chris Palmer said: "Our chief executive Bob
Stubbs met with the director of environmental services at the
council last week and was told that members of the council had
told him to stick to the 30 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
"If they continue with that it means they will reject our
application, and we will have to go to appeal. That would lead to
a 12-month delay and put the completion date back to 2004, but
there is no question of the 2006 World Cup bid being compromised,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
September's World Cup qualifying tie between England and
Germany was to be the old stadium's last match, although that
situation may now change.
</P>
<P>
Construction work has already been put back twice and a plan to
include athletics was ditched last year following a row over the
addition of a running track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
