<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Edges Middlesbrough to Extend Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Manchester
United moved a step closer to their sixth English premier league
title in eight years with a 4-3 victory at Middlesbrough on Monday.
</P>
<P>
United's 22nd victory of the season puts them 11 points clear
of second-placed Liverpool with six matches left to play.
</P>
<P>
England under-21 striker Andy Campbell put the home side in
front in the 19th minute and the game exploded in the second half,
when six goals were scored.
</P>
<P>
Ryan Giggs equalized a minute into the second period before
Andy Cole put United in front on the hour and Paul Scholes struck
a third with a blistering drive from 25 yards.
</P>
<P>
Former United midfielder Paul Ince reduced the deficit four
minutes from time only for substitute Quinton Fortune to restore
United's two-goal advantage almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
The scoring continued up to the final whistle as Middlesbrough
hit back with a goal from substitute Juninho in injury time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0403 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clerides Urges Discussing Core Issues on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
on Tuesday called on the two sides on the divided island to discuss
core issues concerning the reunification of the tiny country.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, leader of the Greek Cypriots who predominantly reside
in the south, made the appeal upon his arrival at the airport in
the southern coast city of Larnaca from visits to the U.S. and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
He said that he and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have
already put forward their positions on the Cyprus issue and given
their clarifications during the first two rounds of U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks in New York and Geneva.
</P>
<P>
They will hold another round of talks in New York on May 23.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the U.S., Clerides met with U.S. Presidential
Emissary for Cyprus Alfred Moses, State Department Coordinator
Thomas Weston and U.N. Secretary-General's special envoy for Cyprus
Alvaro de Soto.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the foreign envoys for Cyprus "all agreed that the
talks beginning on May 23 must be upgraded and the core issues
discussed."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has identified constitution, territory, property and
distribution of powers as the four core issues that need to be
tackled during the talks.
</P>
<P>
Clerides recalled, however, that Denktash repeated during the
two rounds of talks that he refused to negotiate with the Greek
Cypriot side unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus is
recognized.
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign officials have "underlined to both Denktash
and Ankara that they will neither recognize his regime nor
acknowledge it."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally announced the formation of a "
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in November 15, 1983. But it
was recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Clerides noted that if the third round of talks do not bear
fruit "we will reassess the situation."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens
coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0404 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Help to Remove Mines in Arab World Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Arab and international landmine
experts on Tuesday called for more international help to remove
land mines in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made at a three-day regional workshop on mines
hosted by the Arab League here. The experts asked the world
community, the countries planting the mines in particular, to
provide financial and technical support to clear the mines.
</P>
<P>
They said in a final statement that the support was essential "
to heal the problems of the disabled caused by mines and the loss
of human and animal lives and agriculture."
</P>
<P>
Two-fifths of the world's land mines were scattered on Arab
soil, left over from the World War II and the Arab-Israeli
conflicts. Egypt alone has 19.7 million mines laid by Britain,
Germany and Italy in the Western Desert during the world war.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has called on the three countries to provide fund, maps of
mine fields and equipment for mine clearance. It sees their current
aid as meager.
</P>
<P>
A United Nations team visited Egypt in February to assess the
land mine problem, but has yet to release its findings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
