<DOCNO> XIE20000411.0405 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese security authorities have arrested a 10-
member terrorist group linked to the Saudi-expelled billionaire-
terrorist Osama Bin Laden, which was planning a new plot to "
destabilize the country," Daily Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
A judicial source disclosed on Monday that the suspected
terrorists were led by an Egyptian named Jamal Tantawi, who fought
alongside with Bin Laden during the Afghan war in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A military prosecutor has formally charged them with
participation in underground religious extremist cells aimed at
destabilizing the country through terrorist acts, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The source refused to disclose when or where the group members
were arrested. (Lebanon-Terrorist)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli-Syrian peace talks should be conducted
in line with with the relevant United Nations resolutions, and only
in this way can the two sides settle the issue of the Golan
Heights, said a senior Israeli official Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres made the remarks to
Israel Radio, just before Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.
S. President Bill Clinton are scheduled to hold their summit
meeting at the White House in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338 call on, among other things,the
negotiating parties in the Middle East to settle their territorial
disputes under the principle of "land for peace."(Israel-Syria-
Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian team has defined five "Nos" in their
ongoing negotiations with the Israeli side in the United States
Bolling Air Base near Washington, a Palestinian source close to the
talks said.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Arabic daily Al-Aiyam, the source said the five "
NOs" are as follows:
</P>
<P>
- No for giving up any part of the Palestinian territories
seized (by Israel) in the l967 Middle East war, including
Jerusalem;
</P>
<P>
- No for accepting settlement legitimacy;
</P>
<P>
- No for delaying discussions on such issues as Jerusalem and
refugees and for accepting a partial framework agreement;
</P>
<P>
- No for any kind of Israeli military presence inside the
(future) Palestinian State territories from Jordan river border to
joint border with Egypt;
</P>
<P>
- No for the policy of repatriating Palestinian refugees in
places other than their homeland. (Palestinian-Red Lines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's parliament has approved amendments to laws
regulating legislative elections which will take place later this
year with the aim of securing a trouble-free vote, the country's
Middle East News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amendments, approved Monday night by the People's Assembly,
will provide for police to be posted outside each polling station
to prevent intimidation of voters and forestall the kind of
violence that shook previous elections in 1995 when around 60
people died. (Egypt-Law Amendment-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab League has proposed that the Arab countries
convene a summit in March every year, a senior league official said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa al-Fiqqi, Arab League assistant secretary general for
Arab affairs told reporters that the proposal to make a regular
March summit the pan-Arab forum's highest authority would be
discussed on May 24 by the foreign ministers of Egypt, Oman, Syria,
Tunisia and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The five countries form a committee to deal with the issue
concerning the convocation of Arab summits on a regular basis. The
League's 1945 charter does not stipulate the holding of Arab
summits and states that the council of foreign ministers is its
highest body. (Arab League-Summit-Proposal) 
</P>
</TEXT>
