<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Adopt Aggressive Foreign Policy: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia's foreign policy under the
leadership of the newly elected President Vladimir Putin will be
more realistic and "aggressive in the good sense of the word,"
said Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The new foreign policy is expected to be active, constructive,
aimed at solving the global problems facing the international
communities," he told Itar-Tass aboard a plane en route home from
Luxembourg, where he attended a meeting of the Russian-European
Union Cooperation Council.
</P>
<P>
"This policy will be aggressive in the sense of the word. It
will be aggressive where the protection of Russia's interests is
concerned," said Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
However, "it will not be aggressive against anyone, it will be
aggressive for the sake of Russia's interests, to protect the
interests of both Russians and the Russian state, " he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Proceeding from the statements that have been made on top
level,the West understands that Russia's foreign policy will not
be cut off from the country's real life," noted Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the West is interested not only in Russia's
foreign policy but also in its domestic developments and the role
Russia will be playing in international affairs," he added.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that Russia does not refuse integration with
international economic and financial institutions but will be
boosting it.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the Russian newspaper Izvestia in
its Tuesday issue, the minister also summed up the new concept of
Russia's foreign policy, confirming that it will be marked by "
predictability,consistency and pragmatism."
</P>
<P>
"Our foreign policy priorities are now closer linked with long-
term objectives of the country's development and are commensurate
with the state's real potentials and resources," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
Russia will ensure its reliable security by every means to "
shape favorable external conditions for its development, to
influence world processes toward forming a stable, fair and
democratic world structures," and ensure a worthy place for itself
in the world, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
