<HEADLINE> Annan Lauds Disengagement Plan for Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Annan's statement, released at the U.N. headquarters in New
York Tuesday, said it was now the duty of all belligerent military
forces to comply with the decision taken and that they ensure the
security and full freedom of movement of U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
The plan was drawn on April 8 with the assistance of U.N.
Mission in DRC (MONUC) which, together with the Joint Military
Commission established by the Lusaka Agreement, will monitor and
verify the disengagement of forces.
</P>
<P>
Annan said MONUC urgently needs specialized military units to
prepare for the deployment of the 5,500 strong monitoring force.
</P>
<P>
The DRC had since August 1998 been confronted by a rebellion
backed by foreign forces and the government of Kabila also
received military support from several African countries. The
relevant parties signed the Lusaka cease-fire agreement in July
1999. 
</P>
