<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FMs Underscore G-77 Summit's Importance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of Libya and
Sri Lanka underscored on Tuesday here the importance of the South
Summit of the Group of 77 (G-77).
</P>
<P>
Libyan Foreign Minister Abdel Rhaman Shalgam said the present
meeting of G-77  represents an opportunity for developing nations
to face globalization challenges.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting has among its main issues the writing of an
Action Plan which will be approved during the State heads'
sessions and released once its evaluation is finished on April 14.
</P>
<P>
Regarding South-South cooperation one of the main separate
paragraphs to be analyzed here, Libya supported a project based on
its exchange experience with African, Asian and Latin American
countries, besides asking a revaluation of a more just
international financial system.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, after this Summit, it will be necessary to talk
about a brand new G-77, with a most important role to play in
world economy.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, his Sri Lankan counterpart Laksham B.
Kiriella told the press here, that the Summit is a vital need of
the G-77, above all, for its efforts to re-group this organization
's developing members.
</P>
<P>
Kiriella quoted his Cuban counterpart Felipe Perez Roque as
saying that globalization imposed by the developed world tends to
make this world's section even richer, while poverty increases
among the dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's Foreign Minister said that new concentration
mechanisms should be created in order to allow poor nations to
have access the advances in science, technology and knowledge in
general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
