<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries to Cooperate for Better Social Service, Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Cuba said Tuesday that developing
countries have proposed a total of 120 projects for cooperation to
improve social services and agriculture among the South nations.
</P>
<P>
Raul Taldrid, Cuban representative to the South-South
Cooperation Commission, told a press conference here that of the
total, 71 projects were offered by Cuba, a country which attaches
great importance to cooperation among developing countries.
</P>
<P>
These projects are designed to improve agriculture, education,
health, literacy for peoples in developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, currently at issue is how to put money into these
proposed projects, and the foreign ministers of the Group of 77
member states thus agreed to conduct study on how to seek
resources and funds available to finance the projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
After they carry out the study, they will know what to do next,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The press conference was held on the sideline of the South
Summit, the first and largest gathering of heads of state and
government since the founding of the organization in June 1964.
</P>
<P>
Cuba is a country which has a long tradition to aid other
developing countries. In Latin America and the Caribbean, 2,685
Cubans are working on developing programs, in addition to 1,389 in
Africa, 249 in Europe and 36 in Asia, providing assistance in
areas ranging from medicine, education, and construction to sports,
hydroelectricity, agriculture and research.
</P>
<P>
From 1965 to 1998, 37,000 scholarship students from 120
countries graduated from Cuban universities, 13,786 with advanced
degrees. Another 7,090 African workers improved their labor
qualifications through training programs on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's most recent assistance program, which has greatest
resonance for Latin America, is in health arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
