<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Sharply Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) - European stock markets closed
sharply lower Tuesday as a sell-off in high-tech shares in early
trading on Wall Street reinforced the rush out of "new economy"
stocks in Europe.
</P>
<P>
London's benchmark FTSE 100 index led stock markets across the
region lower, falling more than 2.4 percent to 6379.20, a six-week
closing low.
</P>
<P>
Among tech issues tumbling were computer maker Psion, off 14.5
percent, chip designer ARM Holdings, dropping 12.8 percent, and
Internet security provider Baltimore Technology, which shed 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Scottish telecom company Thus fell 9.7 percent, while
Colt Telecom fell 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The pan-European FTSE Europtop 300, a broader index of the
region's largest stocks, was down 1.7 percent at 1599.22, with its
technology, media and telecom segments each shedding more than 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
German technology shares tumbled as the Nasdaq index in the US
dived for the second straight day, sending the Neuer Market down 6.
9 percent and the bluechip DAX down about one percent.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax index ended at 7442.66 points, down 74.29 or 0.99
percent.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, pay-TV operator Canal Plus, Monday's leading gainer
on the CAC-40, fell 7.4 percent, while chipmaker
STMicroelectronics was the leading decliner, falling 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip CAC 40 index fell 1.85 percent to 6247.44, after
a brief rally in late morning ran out of steam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
