<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. FAA Orders Checks of Bolts on Boeing 737 Tail Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) has ordered inspections of bolts on some
Boeing 737 aircraft after loose nuts were found on tail assemblies.
</P>
<P>
The directive, which was issued Monday, said improperly
tightened nuts were found on the elevators of the horizontal
stabilizers on 10 of the aircraft that went into service in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The FAA said a nut coming off could lead to loss of control
during takeoff and landing. The inspections must be completed by
May 25.
</P>
<P>
The nuts "had been finger-tightened but had not been properly
torqued" to meet specifications, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
Since last September, quality control problems, including other
loose nuts and bolts and substandard fasteners, have resulted in
an FAA audit of Boeing and closer scrutiny of suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The latest FAA order covers 737-600s, -700s and -800s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
