<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 120 Million Web Users Worldwide Shop Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 120 million of the
estimated 300 million worldwide Internet users have made a
purchase or transaction online, according to a global study
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The study found that, contrary to popular belief, the vast
majority of the shoppers were satisfied with their online
experience and only a minority voiced concerns about fraud and
security issues. Conducted by San Francisco-based market research
firm Angus Reid Group, the study is based on a sample of more than
28,000 Internet users and consumers in 34 countries in December of
1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, barely half of shoppers outside the U.S.
and Canada use credit cards, compared with 75 percent in North
America. Cash on deliver and bank drafts are almost as popular as
instant credit card payments in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of all Internet users, about 120 million people
worldwide, have made at least one purchase, the study found. More
than half of all online transactions were made in the U.S. The
typical American online shopper made seven purchases over the past
three months for a total of 828 U.S. dollars, compared to the
global average of less than 500 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The most frequently mentioned use of the Internet in relation
to shopping was gathering information about products and services,
done by 52 percent of Internet users. Forty percent have taken the
plunge and purchased a product or service directly online.
</P>
<P>
The goods most frequently purchased online included books,
computer equipment and software or music, and clothing, according
to the study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
