<HEADLINE> Annan Praises Cuba for Achievement in Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday voiced his high evaluation of the Cuban
achievements in education, health and social development, saying
that "Cuba has a lot to share with the other Third World countries.
"
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here overnight to begin his first official
visit to the Caribbean island country as the U.N. chief, made the
statement when meeting teachers and students at the prestigious
Havana University. Annan, who has been in Cuba twice so far, began
his official visit on Tuesday morning, and received a red-carpet
welcome from Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
"Cuba may be among the worst smaller nations in terms of the
population and size, but its geography and history have given it a
special place in the global consciousness," he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing Cuba as a country "under a wide range of embargo
for many years," Annan said the impressive Cuban achievements in
education, health and social achievements are one of the two
factors that took him here at the end of his Europe tour. A second
reason for his current visit is to listen to opinions from Third
World countries in preparation for the Millennium Assembly and
Millennium Summit, scheduled for September in the U.N.
Headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
Annan kicked off his visit to Cuba before his Wednesday
participation in the South Summit, the largest gathering of heads
of state and government since the founding of the Group of 77 in
1964.
</P>
<P>
The Summit, slated for April 10-14, attracts some 60 heads of
state or government and is also the first summit held by the 133-
nation group, currently chaired by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Castro, Cuban Speaker Richardo Alarcon and President of the
Havana University Juan Vela are present at the meeting, during
which Annan fielded questions from journalists and students on the
campus.
</P>
<P>
It is Annan's first official visit to Cuba since he became the
U.N. Secretary-General in 1997. The last U.N. chief to visit the
country was Javier Perez de Cuellar in May 1985.
</P>
<P>
Annan left New York for Geneva on April 3 for Geneva, Rome and
Florence before his arrival in Havana. Annan is expected to return
to New York on April 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
