<HEADLINE> Peru President Fujimori Obtained 49.52 Percent Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 11 (Xinhua)-- Peru's presidential candidate Alberto
Fujimori, has obtained up to now 49.53 percent of votes in Sunday'
s general elections, National Electoral Processes Organization (
NEPO) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
NEPO specified second place is being occupied by candidate of
political grouping "Peru Possible", Alejandro Toledo, with 38.91
percent of votes.
</P>
<P>
During the elections, 14.57 million electors participated to
elect Peru's next president for the next five year.
</P>
<P>
At these elections, Peruvians also voted to elect two vice
Presidents and 120 deputies for the new National Congress.
</P>
<P>
According to NEPO, if none of the presidential candidates
obtains 50 percent plus 1 of votes, Fujimori and Toledo will have
to go to a second election round, to define who will assume
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, who aspires to a third turn of rule, denied that
during elections fraud was concocted as opposition presidential
candidates have been indicating.
</P>
<P>
Despite denouncement of irregularities, the mission of
Organization of American States (OAS) observers has said that in
general Peru's elections are being carried out with complete
normality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
