<HEADLINE> Capital Spending to Jump in U.S., Canada in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Capital and exploration
spending for oil and gas projects in the United States and Canada
will rise sharply this year, a U.S. trade magazine predicted
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Investment outside the U.S. and Canada will decrease, according
to Houston-based Oil &AMP; Gas Journal, which bases its spending
forecasts on an exclusive annual survey of oil and gas companies.
</P>
<P>
Companies this year plan to raise total U.S. spending to 42.6
billion U.S. dollars from 34.9 billion dollars in 1999, a year of
uncertainty about prices of crude oil and natural gas. The
expected 30 percent spending gain follows a 30 percent decrease
last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the U.S. total, spending for exploration and production will
increase to 26 billion dollars in 2000 from 20 billion dollars in
1999. Expected outlays within that category include 21.4 billion
dollars for drilling-exploration, and 4.1 billion dollars for
production. Spending for non-exploration-and-production activities
in the U.S. -- including refining, marketing, petrochemicals and
pipelines -- will increase to 16.6 billion dollars this year from
14.8 billion dollars in 1999, the journal said.
</P>
<P>
Total capital spending in Canada will increase to 17 billion U.
S. dollars from 14.9 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Survey responses from 22 U.S. and Canadian-based companies
indicate spending on projects outside the two countries of 15.9
billion dollars, seven percent less than in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
