<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports Israeli Pullback on Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak won the support for a planned Israeli troop pull out of
southern Lebanon from the Clinton administration when he held
talks with the U.S. Secretary of State on Tuesday, but he was also
pressed to move fast on the Israeli-Palestinian track in the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright praised Barak at a news conference for planning to
pull Israeli troops out of southern Lebanon in July under U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"It is strange that a country is criticized for withdrawing
from another country," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Albright also pressed Barak to move as fast as possible with
the Palestinians toward a West Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"This is an issue that needs to be done as rapidly as possible,
" she said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian negotiations are now under way at the
Bolling Air Force Base near Washington, working on an overall
settlement as well as the Israeli further pullback on the West
Bank scheduled for June.
</P>
<P>
Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO's representative in Washington
disclosed there was still "no results" about the negotiations. "
Let's hope that will change," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said the Palestinians wanted Clinton to make clear to
Barak when they meet this evening that the negotiations between
Israel and the Palestinians must be concluded successfully by
September 13, a deadline set by the United States, Israel and the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
