<HEADLINE> Technology Stocks Fall Sharply Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 11 (Xinhua) -- the technology stocks fell
sharply again Tuesday amid the downbeat earnings reports from two
tech companies, thus eliminating all the Nasdaq index's gains for
the year.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the technology heavy Nasdaq composite
fell 132.30 at 4,055.90. The index is now lower for the year and
is nearly 20 percent below its record closing high of 5,048.62
set March 10.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 100.52 at 11,287.08 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 3.87 at 1,500.59.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq index fell in the second consecutive session today
as Biogen, a leading biotechnology company, reported its first-
quarter earnings of 41 cents a share, below expectations of 43
cents. Biogen fell steeply and other biotech firms also tumbled.
</P>
<P>
The broader technology sector declined after Motorola reported
that its second-quarter and full-year 2000 earnings were expected
to fall short of analysts' expectations after a big earnings
increase in the first-quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index rose because investors once again drew out the
technology sector and moved money into blue chip issues. It's a
rotation back to old reliable stocks from high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 1.49 at 661.20. But the American Stock
Exchange index fell 13.17 at 944.87 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 8.53 at 510.13.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,530 up, 1,456 down and 481
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 967.15 million shares from 850.19
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
