<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Urges Quick Orderly Return of Cuban Boy to Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno Tuesday called for an orderly and quick return of the six-
year-old Cuban boy, Elian Gonzalez, to his father after meeting
two mayors in Miami area.
</P>
<P>
"We all agreed that helping to bring the family together to
work out this orderly transition would be desirable, but I also
stressed that the transfer of Elian to the care of his father must
move forward without delay," Reno said.
</P>
<P>
Reno had a nearly-one-hour meeting with Miami-Dade County Mayor
Alex Penelas and Miami Mayor Joe Carollo.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Reno issued a statement, stressing that
the meeting was "productive" and she "welcomed their suggestions
on how we can best achieve an orderly reunification of Elian with
his father."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Penelas said that the
family should sit down and figure out "what's in the best
interests of the child," adding that Miami community leaders would
accept whatever the family decides.
</P>
<P>
Penelas noted that the issue should be resolved by the family
and a meeting without outsiders should be arranged. "This is a
family decision. It is best made by them," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Carollo told reporters, Reno told them she
also would be willing to meet with Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-
uncle, who is taking care of the boy in Miami.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, Reno also met with Gregory Craig, the U.S.
lawyer for the father, to discuss arrangements for the boy's
transfer.
</P>
<P>
The INS has ruled that the boy belongs to his father, but the
boy's relatives in Florida, backed by some anti-Cuba elements,
insisted the boy stay in the United States. Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, the boy's father, came to the U.S. last week to take
custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
However, Elian, who was rescued on November 25 last year from a
shipwreck after his mother and 11 others died when the boat
capsized in the sea off Florida, was still with the relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
