<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Begins First Official Visit to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Anna
Tuesday kicked off his first official visit to Cuba as the U.N.
chief and spoke highly of the Cuban achievements in social
development.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here overnight and received a red-carpet
welcome from Cuban leader Fidel Castro, said that notwithstanding
the U.S.-imposed embargo for many years, Cuban's achievements are
impressive given its size of gross domestic product per capita.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also touched on the issue of globalization, one
of the major topics under discussion at the current South Summit,
saying the developing countries face many obstacles to their
participation in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Annan is the first U.N. Secretary-General to visit Cuba in 15
years. The last U.N. chief to visit the Caribbean country was
Javier Perez de Cuellar in May 1985.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit is the largest gathering of heads of state
and government in the 36-year history of the Group of 77, which
was set up in Geneva by 77 developing countries. The 133-nation
body is the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations to
negotiate for the collective interests of the developing South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
